# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-society-of-marine-engineers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The **American Federation of Labor** (**A.F. of L.**) was a national federation of labor unions in the United States that continues today as the AFL-CIO.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] It was founded in Columbus, Ohio, in 1886 by an alliance of craft unions eager to provide mutual support and disappointed in the Knights of Labor.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Samuel Gompers was elected the full-time president at its founding convention and was re-elected every year except one until his death in 1924.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] He became the major spokesperson for the union movement.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. was the largest union grouping, even after the creation of the Congress of Industrial Organizations (CIO) by unions that were expelled by the A.F. of L. in 1935.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. was founded and dominated by craft unions, especially in the building trades.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In the late 1930s, craft affiliates expanded by organizing on an industrial union basis to meet the challenge from the CIO.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. and the CIO competed bitterly in the late 1930s but then cooperated during World War II and afterward.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1955, the two merged to create the AFL-CIO, which has comprised the longest lasting and most influential labor federation in the United States to this day.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The American Federation of Labor (A.F. of L.) was organized as an association of trade unions in 1886.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The Federation of Organized Trades and Labor Unions also merged into what would become the American Federation of Labor.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] One of the organizations embroiled in this controversy was the Cigar Makers' International Union (CMIU), a group subject to competition from a dual union, a rival "Progressive Cigarmakers' Union", organized by members suspended or expelled by the CMIU.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The two cigar unions competed with one another in signing contracts with various cigar manufacturers, who were at this same time combining themselves into manufacturers' associations of their own in New York City, Detroit, Cincinnati, Chicago, and Milwaukee.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In January 1886, the Cigar Manufacturers' Association of New York City announced a 20 percent wage cut in factories around the city.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The Cigar Makers' International Union refused to accept the cut and 6,000 of its members in 19 factories were locked out by the owners.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Just when it appeared that the strike might be won, the New York District Assembly of the Knights of Labor leaped into the breach, offering to settle with the 19 factories at a lower wage scale than that proposed by the CMIU, so long as only the Progressive Cigarmakers' Union was employed.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The leadership of the CMIU was enraged and demanded that the New York District Assembly be investigated and punished by the national officials of the Knights of Labor.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The committee of investigation was controlled by individuals friendly to the New York District Assembly, however, and the latter was exonerated.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The American Federation of Labor was thus originally formed as an alliance of craft unions outside the Knights of Labor as a means of defending themselves against this and similar incursions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] On April 25, 1886, a circular letter was issued by Adolph Strasser of the Cigar Makers and P.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] McGuire of the Carpenters, addressed to all national trade unions and calling for their attendance of a conference in Philadelphia on May 18.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Forty-three invitations were mailed, which drew the attendance of 20 delegates and letters of approval from 12 other unions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] For its part, the Knights of Labor considered the demand for the parcelling of the labor movement into narrow craft-based fiefdoms to be anathema, a violation of the principle of solidarity of all workers across craft lines.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Negotiations with the dissident craft unions were nipped in the bud by the governing General Assembly of the K of L, however, with the organization's Grand Master Workman, Terence V.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Powderly refusing to enter into serious discussions on the matter.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The actions of the New York District Assembly of the K of L were upheld.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Revenue for the new organization was to be raised on the basis of a "per-capita tax" of its member organizations, set at the rate of one-half cent per member per month (i.e. six cents per year, equal to $2.15 today).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Governance of the organization was to be by annual conventions, with one delegate allocated for every 4,000 members of each affiliated union.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The founding convention voted to make the President of the new federation a full-time official at a salary of $1,000 per year (equal to $35,833 today), and Samuel Gompers of the Cigar Makers' International Union was elected to the position.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Gompers would ultimately be re-elected to the position by annual conventions of the organization for every year save one until his death nearly four decades later.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Although the founding convention of the A.F. of L. had authorized the establishment of a publication for the new organization, Gompers made use of the existing labor press to generate support for the position of the craft unions against the Knights of Labor.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Headway was made in the form of endorsement by various local labor bodies.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Some assemblies of the K of L supported the Cigar Makers' position and departed the organization: in Baltimore, 30 locals left the organization, while the membership of the Knights in Chicago fell from 25,000 in 1886 to just 3,500 in 1887.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Factional warfare broke out in the K of L, with Terence Powderly blaming the organization's travails on "radicals" in its ranks, while those opposing Powderly called for an end to what they perceived as "autocratic leadership".
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In the face of the steady disintegration of its rival, the fledgling American Federation of Labor struggled to maintain itself, with the group showing very slow and incremental growth in its first years, only cracking the 250,000 member mark in 1892.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The group from the outset concentrated upon the income and working conditions of its membership as its almost sole focus.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] This fundamentally conservative "pure and simple" approach limited the A.F. of L. to matters pertaining to working conditions and rates of pay, relegating political goals to its allies in the political sphere.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The Federation favored pursuit of workers' immediate demands rather than challenging the property rights of owners, and took a pragmatic view of politics which favored tactical support for particular politicians over formation of a party devoted to workers' interests.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L.'s leadership believed the expansion of the capitalist system was seen as the path to betterment of labor, an orientation making it possible for the A.F. of L. to present itself as what one historian has called "the conservative alternative to working class radicalism".
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. faced its first major reversal when employers launched an open shop movement in 1903, designed to drive unions out of construction, mining, longshore and other industries.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Membership in the A.F. of L.'s affiliated unions declined between 1904 and 1914 in the face of this concerted anti-union drive, which made effective use of legal injunctions against strikes, court rulings given force when backed with the armed might of the state.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] At its November 1907 Convention in Norfolk, Virginia, the A.F. of L. founded the future North America's Building Trades Unions (NABTU) as its Department of Building Trades.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Ever the pragmatist, Gompers argued that labor should "reward its friends and punish its enemies" in both major parties.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] However, in the 1900s (decade), the two parties began to realign, with the main faction of the Republican Party coming to identify with the interests of banks and manufacturers, while a substantial portion of the rival Democratic Party took a more labor-friendly position.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] While not precluding its members from belonging to the Socialist Party or working with its members, the A.F. of L. traditionally refused to pursue the tactic of independent political action by the workers in the form of the existing Socialist Party or the establishment of a new labor party.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] After 1908, the organization's tie to the Democratic party grew increasingly strong.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Some unions within the A.F. of L. helped form and participated in the National Civic Federation.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The National Civic Federation was formed by several progressive employers who sought to avoid labor disputes by fostering collective bargaining and "responsible" unionism.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Major Republican leaders, such as President William McKinley and Senator Mark Hanna, made pro-labor statements.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Labor's participation in the National Civic Federation created internal division within the A.F. of L.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The Socialist element who believed the only way to help workers was to remove large industry from private ownership, denounced labor's efforts at cooperation with the capitalists.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. nonetheless continued its association with the group, which declined in importance as the decade of the 1910s drew to a close.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] By the 1890s, Gompers was planning an international federation of labor, starting with the expansion of A.F. of L. affiliates in Canada, especially Ontario.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] He helped the Canadian Trades and Labour Congress with money and organizers, and by 1902, the A.F. of L. came to dominate the Canadian union movement.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. vigorously opposed unrestricted immigration from Europe for moral, cultural, and racial reasons.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The issue unified the workers who feared that an influx of new workers would flood the labor market and lower wages.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Nativism was not a factor because upwards of half the union members were themselves immigrants or the sons of immigrants from Ireland, Germany and Britain.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Nativism was a factor when the A.F. of L. even more strenuously opposed all immigration from Asia because it represented (to its Euro-American members) an alien culture that could not be assimilated into American society.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. intensified its opposition after 1906 and was instrumental in passing immigration restriction bills from the 1890s to the 1920s, such as the 1921 Emergency Quota Act and the Immigration Act of 1924, and seeing that they were strictly enforced.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Mink (1986) concludes that the link between the A.F. of L. and the Democratic Party rested in part on immigration issues, noting the large corporations, which supported the Republicans, wanted more immigration to augment their labor force.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Prohibition gained strength as the German American community came under fire.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. was against prohibition as it was viewed as cultural right of the working class to drink.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Child labor was an issue on which the A.F. of L. found common ground with middle class reformers who otherwise kept their distance.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. joined campaigns at the state and national level to limit the employment of children under age 14.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1904 a major national organization emerged, the National Child Labor Committee (NCLC).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In state after state reformers launched crusades to pass laws restricting child labor, with the ultimate goals of rescuing young bodies and increasing school attendance.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The frustrations included the Supreme Court striking down two national laws as unconstitutional, and weak enforcement of state laws due to the political influence of employers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. and its affiliates were strong supporters of the war effort.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The risk of disruptions to war production by labor radicals provided the A.F. of L. political leverage to gain recognition and mediation of labor disputes, often in favor of improvements for workers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. unions avoided strikes in favor of arbitration.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Wages soared as near-full employment was reached at the height of the war.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. unions strongly encouraged young men to enlist in the military, and fiercely opposed efforts to reduce recruiting and slow war production by pacifists, the anti-war Industrial Workers of the World (IWW) and the radical faction of Socialists.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] To keep factories running smoothly, President Wilson established the National War Labor Board in 1918, which forced management to negotiate with existing unions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Wilson also appointed A.F. of L. president Gompers to the powerful Council of National Defense, where he set up the War Committee on Labor.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] F. of L. was strongly committed to the national war aims and cooperated closely with Washington.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] It used the opportunity to grow rapidly.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Gompers chaired the wartime Labor Advisory Board.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] He attended the Paris Peace Conference in 1919 as an official advisor on labor issues.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1920, the A.F. of L. petitioned Washington for the release of prisoners who had been convicted under Wartime Emergency Laws.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Wilson did not act but President Warren Harding did so.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] While 1919 was the first year of peace after the end of the First World War, it was a year of great turmoil in the US labor movement.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] A.F. of L. membership soared to 2.4 million in 1917 and 4.1 million at the end of 1919.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. unions tried to make their gains permanent and called a series of major strikes in meat, steel, and other industries.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] This was coupled with the First Red Scare, which feared a workers' revolution in the image of the Russian Revolution in the US.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] While the Red Scare centered its attacks on more radical unions, such as the IWW, the AFL was also subject to repression from both the government and various vigilante groups such as the American Legion.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] 1919 was also a decisive year in the AFL's tumultuous relationship to the ever-growing population of black industrial workers, a result of the Great Migration.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Due to jobs being taken away from soldiers fighting in Europe and given, largely, to black workers new to the Northern states, many returning white soldiers laid the blame for their economic uncertainty on the black workers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] This caused increased racial tension across the country, which, when coupled with the nationalism stoked by the war, led to the Red Summer, a series of outbreaks of mass racial violence that not only targeted black people in general but also organized workers broadly.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The AFL did little to aid the black workers trying to hold on to a peaceful existence in the north and did less to protest the increasingly cruel treatment of black workers in the Deep South made painful apparent by the Elaine Massacre.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The failure of the AFL to deal with the Red Scare, racial issues, and generally capitalize on the momentum of the militant organizing that dominated the year 1919 after the Seattle General Strike led to a decline in the organization's prestige and respect among workers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] This left them open to being ravaged by open shop drives which intensified in the wake of 1919.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In the pro-business environment of the 1920s, business launched a large-scale offensive on behalf of the so-called "open shop", which meant that a person did not have to be a union member to be hired.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] A.F. of L. unions lost membership steadily until 1933.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1924, following the death of Samuel Gompers, UMWA member and A.F. of L. vice president William Green became the president of the labor federation.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The organization endorsed pro-labor Progressive candidate Robert M.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] La Follette in the 1924 presidential election.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] He only carried his home state of Wisconsin.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The campaign failed to establish a permanent independent party closely connected to the labor movement, however, and thereafter the Federation embraced ever more closely the Democratic Party, despite the fact that many union leaders remained Republicans.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Herbert Hoover in 1928 won the votes of many Protestant A.F. of L. members.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The Great Depression were hard times for the unions, and membership fell sharply across the country.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] As the national economy began to recover in 1933, so did union membership.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Roosevelt, a Democrat, strongly favored labor unions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] He made sure that relief operations like the Civilian Conservation Corps did not include a training component that would produce skilled workers who would compete with union members in a still glutted market.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The major legislation was the National Labor Relations Act of 1935, called the Wagner Act.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] It greatly strengthened organized unions, especially by weakening the company unions that many workers belonged to.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] It was to the members advantage to transform a company union into a local of an A.F. of L. union, and thousands did so, dramatically boosting the membership.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The Wagner Act also set up to the National Labor Relations Board, which used its powers to rule in favor of unions and against the companies.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In the early 1930s, A.F. of L. president William Green (president, 1924–1952) experimented with an industrial approach to organizing in the automobile and steel industries.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. made forays into industrial unionism by chartering federal labor unions, which would organize across an industry and be chartered by the Federation, not through existing craft unions, guilds, or brotherhoods.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] As early as 1923, the A.F. of L. had chartered federal labor unions, including six news writer locals that had formerly been part of the International Typographical Union.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] However, in the 1930s the A.F. of L. began chartering these federal labor unions as an industrial organizing strategy.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The dues in these federal labor unions (FLUs) were kept intentionally low to make them more accessible to low paid industrial workers; however, these low dues later allowed the Internationals in the Federation to deny members of FLUs voting membership at conventions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1933, Green sent William Collins to Detroit to organize automobile workers into a federal labor union.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] That same year workers at the Westinghouse plant in East Springfield MA, members of federal labor union 18476, struck for recognition.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1933, the A.F. of L. received 1,205 applications for charters for federal labor unions, 1006 of which were granted.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] By 1934, the A.F. of L. had successfully organized 32,500 autoworkers using the federal labor union model.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Most of the leadership of the craft union internationals that made up the federation, advocated for the FLU's to be absorbed into existing craft union internationals and for these internationals to have supremacy of jurisdiction.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1934, one hundred FLUs met separately and demanded that the A.F. of L. continue to issue charters to unions organizing on an industrial basis independent of the existing craft union internationals.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1935 the FLUs representing autoworkers and rubber workers both held conventions independent of the craft union internationals.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] By the 1935 A.F. of L. convention, Green and the advocates of traditional craft unionism faced increasing dissension led by John L.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Lewis of the coal miners, Sidney Hillman of the Amalgamated, David Dubinsky of the Garment Workers, Charles Howard of the ITU, Thomas McMahon of the Textile Workers, and Max Zaritsky of the Hat, Cap, and Millinery Workers, in addition to the members of the FLU's themselves.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Lewis argued that the A.F.of L. was too heavily oriented toward traditional craftsmen, and was overlooking the opportunity to organize millions of semiskilled workers, especially those in industrial factories that made automobiles, rubber, glass and steel.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1935 Lewis led the dissenting unions in forming a new Congress for Industrial Organization (CIO) within the A.F. of L.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Both the new CIO industrial unions, and the older A.F. of L. crafts unions grew rapidly after 1935.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] He won reelection in a landslide in 1936, and by a closer margin in 1940.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Labor unions gave strong support in 1940, compared to very strong support in 1936.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The Gallup Poll showed CIO voters declined from 85% in 1935 to 79% in 1940.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Other union members went from 74% to 57%.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Blue collar workers who were not union members went 72% to 64%.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. retained close ties to the Democratic machines in big cities through the 1940s.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Its membership surged during the war and it held on to most of its new members after wartime legal support for labor was removed.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Despite its close connections to many in Congress, the A.F. of L. was not able to block the Taft–Hartley Act in 1947.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Also in 1947, the union supported the strike efforts of thousands of switchboard operators by donating thousands of dollars.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1955, the A.F. of L. and CIO merged to form the AFL-CIO, headed by George Meany.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] During its first years, the A.F. of L. admitted nearly anyone.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Gompers opened the A.F. of L. to radical and socialist workers and to some semiskilled and unskilled workers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Women, African Americans, and immigrants joined in small numbers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] By the 1890s, the Federation had begun to organize only skilled workers in craft unions and became an organization of mostly white men.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Although the A.F. of L. preached a policy of egalitarianism in regard to African-American workers, it actively discriminated against them.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. sanctioned the maintenance of segregated locals within its affiliates, particularly in the construction and railroad industries, a practice that often excluded black workers altogether from union membership and thus from employment in organized industries.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] These practices led prominent labor historian Philip S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1901, the A.F. of L. lobbied Congress to reauthorize the 1882 Chinese Exclusion Act, and issued a pamphlet entitled "Some reasons for Chinese Exclusion.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] American Manhood against Asiatic Coolieism.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. also began one of the first organized labor boycotts when they began putting white stickers on the cigars made by unionized white cigar rollers while simultaneously discouraging consumers from purchasing cigars rolled by Chinese workers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In general, AFL unions preferred native-born workers, discouraged the speaking of any language other than English by its members, and had strict citizenship requirements of the immigrants it did admit to the union for the majority of its history.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In most ways, the A.F. of L.'s treatment of women workers paralleled its policy towards black workers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. never adopted a strict policy of gender exclusion and, at times, even came out in favor of women's unionism.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] However, despite such rhetoric, it only half-heartedly supported women's attempts to organize and, more often, took pains to keep women out of unions and the workforce altogether.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Only two national unions affiliated with the A.F. of L. at its founding openly included women, and others passed bylaws barring women's membership entirely.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. hired its first female organizer, Mary Kenney O'Sullivan, only in 1892, released her after five months, and it did not replace her or hire another woman national organizer until 1908.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Women who organized their own unions were often turned down in bids to join the Federation, and even women who did join unions found them hostile or intentionally inaccessible.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Unions often held meetings at night or in bars when women might find it difficult to attend and where they might feel uncomfortable, and male unionists heckled women who tried to speak at meetings.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Generally, the A.F. of L. viewed women workers as competition, strikebreakers, or an unskilled labor reserve that kept wages low.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] As such, it often opposed women's employment entirely.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] When it organized women workers, it most often did so to protect men's jobs and earning power, not to improve the conditions, lives, or wages of women workers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In response, most women workers remained outside the labor movement.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1900, only 3.3% of working women were organized into unions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1910, even as the A.F. of L. surged forward in membership, that number had dipped to 1.5%.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] It improved to 6.6% over the next decade, but women remained mostly outside of unions and practically invisible inside of them into the mid-1920s.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Attitudes gradually changed within the A.F. of L. by the pressure of organized female workers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Female-domination began to emerge in the first two decades of the 20th century, including particularly the International Ladies Garment Workers' Union.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Women organized independent locals among New York hat makers, in the Chicago stockyards, and among Jewish and Italian waist makers, to name only three examples.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Through the efforts of middle-class reformers and activists, often of the Women's Trade Union League, those unions joined the A.F. of L.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In some cases, the A.F. of L. mediated the dispute, usually by favoring the larger or more influential union.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. often reversed its jurisdictional rulings over time, as the continuing jurisdictional battles between the Brewers and the Teamsters showed.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Affiliates within the AFL formed "departments" to help resolve these jurisdictional conflicts and to provide a more effective voice for member unions in given industries.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The Metal Trades Department engaged in some organizing of its own, primarily in shipbuilding, where unions such as the Pipefitters, Machinists and Iron Workers joined through local metal workers' councils to represent a diverse group of workers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The Railway Employes' Department dealt with both jurisdictional disputes between affiliates and pursued a common legislative agenda for all of them.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. made efforts in its early years to assist its affiliates in organizing: it advanced funds or provided organizers or, in some cases, such as the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, the Teamsters and the American Federation of Musicians, helped form the union.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. also chartered "federal unions", local unions not affiliated with any international union, in those fields in which no affiliate claimed jurisdiction.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. also encouraged the formation of local labor bodies, known as central labor councils, in major metropolitan areas in which all of the affiliates could participate.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Those local labor councils acquired a great deal of influence in some cases.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] For example, the Chicago Federation of Labor spearheaded efforts to organize packinghouse and steel workers during and immediately after World War I.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Local building trades councils also became powerful in some areas.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In San Francisco, the local Building Trades Council, led by Carpenters official P.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] McCarthy, not only dominated the local labor council but helped elect McCarthy mayor of San Francisco in 1909.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In a very few cases early in the A.F. of L.'s history, state and local bodies defied A.F. of L. policy or chose to disaffiliate over policy disputes.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Though Gompers had contact with socialists and such as A.F. of L. co-founder Peter J.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] McGuire, the A.F. of L. adopted a philosophy of "business unionism" that emphasized unions' contribution to businesses' profits and national economic growth.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The business unionist approach also focused on skilled workers' immediate job-related interests, while refusing to "rush to the support of any one of the numerous society-saving or society destroying schemes" involved in larger political issues.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] This approach was set by Gompers, who was influenced by a fellow cigar maker (and former socialist) Ferdinand Laurrel.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Despite his socialist contacts, Gompers himself was not a socialist.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Employers discovered the efficacy of labor injunctions, first used with great effect by the Cleveland administration during the Pullman Strike in 1894.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. thought that it had achieved the latter with the passage of the Clayton Antitrust Act in 1914—which Gompers referred to as "Labor's Magna Carta".
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] 443 (1921), the United States Supreme Court narrowly read the Act and codified the federal courts' existing power to issue injunctions rather than limit it.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The court read the phrase "between an employer and employees" (contained in the first paragraph of the Act) to refer only to cases involving an employer and its own employees, leaving the courts free to punish unions for engaging in sympathy strikes or secondary boycotts.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L.'s pessimistic attitude towards politics did not, on the other hand, prevent affiliated unions from pursuing their own agendas.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Construction unions supported legislation that governed entry of contractors into the industry and protected workers' rights to pay, rail and mass production industries sought workplace safety legislation, and unions generally agitated for the passage of workers' compensation statutes.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] At the same time, the A.F. of L. took efforts on behalf of women in supporting protective legislation.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] It advocated fewer hours for women workers, and based its arguments on assumptions of female weakness.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Like efforts to unionize, most support for protective legislation for women came out of a desire to protect men's jobs.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] If women's hours could be limited, reasoned A.F. of L. officials, they would infringe less on male employment and earning potential.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] But the A.F. of L. also took more selfless efforts.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Even from the 1890s, the A.F. of L. declared itself vigorously in favor of women's suffrage.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] It often printed pro-suffrage articles in its periodical, and in 1918, it supported the National Union of Women's Suffrage.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. relaxed its rigid stand against legislation after the death of Gompers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Its proposals for unemployment benefits (made in the late 1920s) were too modest to have practical value, as the Great Depression soon showed.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The impetus for the major federal labor laws of the 1930s came from the New Deal.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The enormous growth in union membership came after Congress passed the National Industrial Recovery Act in 1933 and National Labor Relations Act in 1935.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. refused to sanction or participate in the mass strikes led by John L.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Lewis of the United Mine Workers and other left unions such as the Amalgamated Clothing Workers of America.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] After the A.F. of L. expelled the CIO in 1936, the CIO undertook a major organizing effort.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1947, when the Taft-Hartley Act was passed, political activities were stirred.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In resistance to the new law, the CIO joined the A.F. of L., and political co-operation set the path for union unity.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The two groups merged, eight years later, into the AFL–CIO coalition with George Meany as the new president.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] The **American Society of Marine Engineers** (abbr: **ASME**) was a company union established by shipowners in 1921 to supplant or weaken the chief labor union of American marine engineers, the Marine Engineers' Beneficial Association (MEBA).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] The ASME enjoyed some success for a number of years after the failed MEBA strike of 1921, but was effectively eliminated as a competitor to MEBA following the successful "Big Strike" of 1934.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] The ASME also served as an educational organization, and continued publishing its official organ, *The Log*, until 1941.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] During World War I, the United States merchant navy underwent a great expansion, leading to a shortage of qualified marine engineers, which in turn led to an increase in wages.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] The situation was reversed in the postwar period, with a surplus of engineers seeking a reduced number of jobs.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] In 1921, shipowners attempted to take advantage of these conditions by reducing wages, in response to which, the chief trade union representing American marine engineers, the Marine Engineers' Beneficial Association (MEBA), went on strike.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] With the union unable to exert leverage due to the high number of unemployed in the industry, the strike was a disastrous failure for MEBA, which lost half its membership in the aftermath.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] In the wake of the failed strike, shipowners sought to consolidate their victory over MEBA by establishing a number of company unions to replace it.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] The most important of these was the American Society of Marine Engineers (ASME).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] The American Society of Marine Engineers was established in San Francisco, California, in 1921.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] A tenet of its constitution was to avoid affiliation with organized labor groups, such as the American Federation of Labor.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] The ASME did not concern itself with the working conditions or wages of its members, or with improving their material condition, as a result of which, it was not considered a bona fide labor union by the federal government.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] Because of the failed 1921 strike, however, many marine engineers were nonetheless compelled to resign from MEBA and join ASME as a condition for obtaining employment in the industry.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] In addition to its other activities, the ASME also worked to improve professional standards and methods within the profession, and on influencing legislation dealing with it.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] An auxiliary membership was made available to machinists, who could improve their knowledge with free access to the Society's extensive library of marine engineering textbooks in preparation for licence examinations.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] Auxiliary members were also assisted in gaining work experience aboard ships.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] Free weekly lectures on marine engineering topics were organized, and published in the Society's weekly journal, *The Log*.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] By 1934, the Society claimed a membership of 800.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] On 9 May 1934, the International Longshoremen's Association went on strike, and was joined on 15 May by the Sailor's Union on the Pacific.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] The Marine Engineers' Beneficial Association, "on the verge of extinction and with nothing to lose", joined the "Big Strike" on the 19th.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] This time, the strike was successful, with the shipowners' associations agreeing to recognize and negotiate with MEBA.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] As a result of the union victory, membership in the ASME collapsed virtually overnight, with most of its members flocking back to MEBA.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] The ASME's activities were further restricted in 1935 by the National Labor Relations Act, which outlawed company unions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] The ASME continued to engage in educational activities, publishing its official organ *The Log* until 1941, when the magazine was sold to Miller Freeman Publications.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-marine-engineers] In January 1951, *The Log* incorporated another magazine, *Pacific Marine Review*.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Prior to European colonization, California was one of the most culturally and linguistically diverse areas in pre-Columbian North America.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] European exploration in the 16th and 17th centuries led to the colonization by the Spanish Empire.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The area became a part of Mexico in 1821, as a result of its successful war for independence.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Following the U.S. conquest of California, part of the Mexican-American War, California was ceded to the United States in 1848.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The California gold rush started in 1848 and led to social and demographic changes, including the California genocide.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] It organized itself and was admitted as the 31st state in 1850 as a free state, following the Compromise of 1850.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Greater Los Angeles, the Inland Empire, and the San Francisco Bay Area are the nation's second, twelfth, and thirteenth most populous metropolitan areas.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Los Angeles is the state's most populous city and is ranked second in population in the nation.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Part of the Californias region of North America, the state's diverse geography ranges from the Pacific Coast and metropolitan areas in the west to the Sierra Nevada mountains in the east, and from the redwood and Douglas fir forests in the northwest to the Mojave Desert in the southeast.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Two-thirds of the nation's earthquake risk lies in California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The Central Valley, a fertile agricultural area, dominates the state's center.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The large size of the state results in climates that vary from moist temperate rainforest in the north to arid desert in the interior, as well as snowy alpine in the mountains.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] While California is warming and drying overall, with frequent wildfires, the state is also experiencing increasing weather whiplash.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The economy of California is the largest of any U.S. state, with an estimated 2025 gross state product of $4.296 trillion as of Q3 2025.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] It is also the world's largest sub-national economy and, if it were an independent country, would be the fourth-largest economy in the world (behind Germany and ahead of Japan) by nominal GDP as of 2025.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The state's agricultural industry leads the nation in output, fueled by its production of dairy, almonds, and grapes.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Despite heavy reliance on seaborne foreign crude oil, California also refines some of its own oil, primarily drilled from Kern County.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] With the busiest port in the country (Los Angeles), California plays a pivotal role in the global supply chain, hauling in about 40% of goods imported to the US.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Notable contributions to popular culture, ranging from entertainment, sports, music, and fashion, have their origins in California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Despite an exodus of filmmaking from California, Hollywood continues to be an important center of the U.S. film industry, one of the oldest and largest film industries in the world; profoundly influencing global entertainment since the 1920s.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The San Francisco Bay Area's Silicon Valley is the center of the global technology industry.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The Spaniards gave the name *Las Californias* to the peninsula of Baja California (in modern-day Mexico).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] As Spanish explorers and settlers moved north and inland, the region known as "California", or "Las Californias", grew in both area and population.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Eventually it included lands north of the peninsula, Alta California, part of which became the present-day U.S. state of California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] A 2017 state legislative document stated, "Numerous theories exist as to the origin and meaning of the word 'California'", and that all anyone knows is the name was added to a map by 1541 "presumably by a Spanish navigator".
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The name is most likely derived from the mythical island of California in the fictional story of Queen Calafia, as recorded in a 1510 work *The Adventures of Esplandián* by Garci Rodríguez de Montalvo.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Queen Calafia's kingdom was said to be a remote land rich in gold and pearls, inhabited by beautiful dark-skinned women who wore gold armor and lived like Amazons, and bred griffins for war.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Abbreviations of the state's name include CA, Cal, Cali, Calif, and US-CA.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] California was one of the most culturally and linguistically diverse areas in pre-Columbian North America.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Historians generally agree that there were at least 300,000 people living in California prior to European colonization.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The Indigenous peoples of California included more than 70 distinct ethnic groups, inhabiting environments ranging from mountains and deserts to islands and redwood forests.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Living in these diverse geographic areas, the indigenous peoples developed complex forms of ecosystem management, including forest gardening to ensure the regular availability of important food sources and medicinal plants.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] This was a form of sustainable agriculture.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] To mitigate destructive large wildfires from ravaging the natural environment, indigenous peoples developed a practice of controlled burning.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] This practice was recognized for its benefits by the California government in 2022.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] These groups were also diverse in their political organization, with bands, tribes, villages, and, on the resource-rich coasts, large chiefdoms, such as the Chumash, Pomo and Salinan.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Trade, intermarriage, craft specialists, and military alliances fostered social and economic relationships between many groups.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Although nations would sometimes war, most armed conflicts were between groups of men for vengeance.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Acquiring territory was not usually the purpose of these small-scale battles.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Men and women generally had different roles in society.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Women were often responsible for weaving, harvesting, processing, and preparing food, while men for hunting and other forms of physical labor.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Most societies also had roles for people whom the Spanish referred to as *joyas*, who they saw as "men who dressed as women".
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] *Joyas* were responsible for death, burial, and mourning rituals, and they performed women's social roles.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Indigenous societies had terms such as two-spirit to refer to them.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The Chumash referred to them as *'aqi.* The early Spanish settlers detested and sought to eliminate them.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The first Europeans to explore the coast of California were the members of a Spanish maritime expedition led by Portuguese captain Juan Rodríguez Cabrillo in 1542.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Cabrillo was commissioned by Antonio de Mendoza, the Viceroy of New Spain, to lead an expedition up the Pacific coast in search of trade opportunities; they entered San Diego Bay on September 28, 1542, and reached at least as far north as San Miguel Island.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Privateer and explorer Francis Drake explored and claimed an undefined portion of the California coast in 1579, landing north of the future city of San Francisco.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The first documented Asians to set foot on what is now the United States occurred in 1587, when Filipino sailors arrived in Spanish ships at Morro Bay.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Descendants of the Islamic Caliph Hasan ibn Ali, who had been living in formerly Muslim Manila, transited through California while traveling to Guerrero, Mexico.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] These individuals, who had converted to Christianity while retaining some Islamic traditions, later played a role in Mexico's wars of independence.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Sebastián Vizcaíno explored and mapped the coast of California in 1602 for New Spain, putting ashore in Monterey.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Despite the on-the-ground explorations of California in the 16th century, Rodríguez's idea of California as an island persisted.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Such depictions appeared on many European maps well into the 18th century.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The Portolá expedition of 1769–70 was a pivotal event in the Spanish colonization of California, resulting in the establishment of numerous missions, presidios, and pueblos.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The military and civil contingent of the expedition was led by Gaspar de Portolá, who traveled over land from Sonora into California, while the religious component was headed by Junípero Serra, who came by sea from Baja California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] In 1769, Portolá and Serra established Mission San Diego de Alcalá and the Presidio of San Diego, the first religious and military settlements founded by the Spanish in California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] By the end of the expedition in 1770, they would establish the Presidio of Monterey and Mission San Carlos Borromeo de Carmelo on Monterey Bay.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] After the Portolà expedition, Spanish missionaries led by Father-President Serra set out to establish 21 Spanish missions of California along El Camino Real ("The Royal Road") and along the California coast, 16 sites of which having been chosen during the Portolá expedition.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Numerous major cities in California grew out of missions, including San Francisco (Mission San Francisco de Asís), San Diego (Mission San Diego de Alcalá), Ventura (Mission San Buenaventura), and Santa Barbara (Mission Santa Barbara), among others.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Juan Bautista de Anza led a significant expedition throughout California in 1775–76, which would extend deeper into the interior and north of California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The Anza expedition selected numerous sites for missions, presidios, and pueblos, which subsequently would be established by settlers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Gabriel Moraga, a member of the expedition, would also christen many of California's prominent rivers with their names in 1775–1776, such as the Sacramento River and the San Joaquin River.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] After the expedition, Gabriel's son, José Joaquín Moraga, would found the pueblo of San Jose in 1777, making it the first civilian-established city in California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] During this same period, sailors from the Russian Empire explored along the northern coast of California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] In 1812, the Russian-American Company established a trading post and small fortification at Fort Ross on the North Coast.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Fort Ross was primarily used to supply Russia's Alaskan colonies with food supplies.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The settlement did not meet much success, failing to attract settlers or establish long term trade viability, and was abandoned by 1841.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] During the War of Mexican Independence, Alta California was largely unaffected and uninvolved in the revolution, though many Californios supported independence from Spain, which many believed had neglected California and limited its development.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Spain's trade monopoly on California had limited local trade prospects.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Following Mexican independence, California ports were freely able to trade with foreign merchants.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Governor Pablo Vicente de Solá presided over the transition from Spanish colonial rule to independent Mexican rule.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] In 1821, the Mexican War of Independence gave the Mexican Empire (which included California) independence from Spain.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] In 1822, the California's first legislature was formed, known as the Diputación de Alta California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The California mission system, which controlled much of the best land in Alta California, was secularized by 1834 and became the property of the Mexican government.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The governor granted many square leagues of land to others with political influence.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] These huge *ranchos* or cattle ranches emerged as the dominant institutions of Mexican California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The ranchos developed under ownership by Californios (Hispanics native of California) who traded cowhides and tallow with Boston merchants.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Beef did not become a commodity until the 1849 California Gold Rush.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] From the 1820s, trappers and settlers from the U.S. and Canada began to arrive in Northern California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] These new arrivals used the Siskiyou Trail, California Trail, Oregon Trail and Old Spanish Trail to cross the rugged mountains and harsh deserts in and surrounding California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The early government of the newly independent Mexico was highly unstable, and in a reflection of this, from 1831 onwards, California also experienced a series of armed disputes, both internal and with the central Mexican government.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] During this tumultuous political period Juan Bautista Alvarado was able to secure the governorship during 1836–1842.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The military action which first brought Alvarado to power had momentarily declared California to be an independent state, and had been aided by Anglo-American residents of California, including Isaac Graham.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] In 1840, one hundred of those residents who did not have passports were arrested, leading to the Graham Affair, which was resolved in part with the intercession of Royal Navy officials.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] One of the largest ranchers in California was John Marsh.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] After failing to obtain justice against squatters on his land from the Mexican courts, he determined that California should become part of the United States.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Marsh conducted a letter-writing campaign espousing the California climate, the soil, and other reasons to settle there, as well as the best route to follow, which became known as "Marsh's route".
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] His letters were read, reread, passed around, and printed in newspapers throughout the country, and started the first wagon trains rolling to California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] After ushering in the period of organized emigration to California, Marsh became involved in a military battle between the much-hated Mexican general, Manuel Micheltorena and the California governor he had replaced, Juan Bautista Alvarado.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] At the Battle of Providencia near Los Angeles, he convinced each side that they had no reason to be fighting each other.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] As a result of Marsh's actions, they abandoned the fight, Micheltorena was defeated, and California-born Pio Pico was returned to the governorship.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] This paved the way for California's ultimate acquisition by the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] In 1846, a group of American settlers in and around Sonoma rebelled against Mexican rule during the Bear Flag Revolt.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Afterward, rebels raised the Bear Flag (featuring a bear, a star, a red stripe and the words "California Republic") at Sonoma.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The Republic's only president was William B.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Ide, who played a pivotal role during the Bear Flag Revolt.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] This revolt by American settlers served as a prelude to the later American military invasion of California and was closely coordinated with nearby American military commanders.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The California Republic was short-lived; the same year marked the outbreak of the Mexican–American War (1846–1848).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Navy sailed into Monterey Bay in 1846 and began the U.S. military invasion of California, with Northern California capitulating in less than a month to the U.S. forces.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] In Southern California, Californios continued to resist American forces.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Notable military engagements of the conquest include the Battle of San Pasqual and the Battle of Dominguez Rancho in Southern California, as well as the Battle of Olómpali and the Battle of Santa Clara in Northern California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] After a series of defensive battles in the south, the Treaty of Cahuenga was signed by the Californios on January 13, 1847, securing a censure and establishing de facto American control in California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The even more lightly populated and arid lower region of old Baja California remained as a part of Mexico.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] In 1846, the total settler population of the western part of the old Alta California had been estimated to be no more than 8,000, plus about 100,000 Native Americans, down from about 300,000 before Hispanic settlement in 1769.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] In 1848, gold was discovered at Sutter's Mill, just weeks prior to the formal transfer of California to the United States under the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] This monumental event triggered the California gold rush—one of the largest mass migrations in modern history.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The ensuing population boom permanently transformed the region's economy and demographics, as hundreds of thousands of fortune-seekers from the eastern United States, Europe, Latin America, and Asia flooded the territory.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] By the time of California's application for statehood in 1850, the settler population of California had multiplied to 100,000.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Between 1847 and 1870, the population of San Francisco increased from 500 to 150,000.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The seat of government for California under Spanish and later Mexican rule had been located in Monterey from 1777 until 1845.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Pio Pico, the last Mexican governor of Alta California, had briefly moved the capital to Los Angeles in 1845.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The U.S. consulate had also been located in Monterey, under consul Thomas O.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] In 1849, a state Constitutional Convention was first held in Monterey.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Among the first tasks of the convention was a decision on a location for the new state capital.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The first full legislative sessions were held in San Jose (1850–1851).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Subsequent locations included Vallejo (1852–1853), and nearby Benicia (1853–1854); these locations eventually proved to be inadequate as well.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The capital has been located in Sacramento since 1854 with only a short break in 1862 when legislative sessions were held in San Francisco due to flooding in Sacramento.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Once the state's Constitutional Convention had finalized its state constitution, it applied to the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] On September 9, 1850, as part of the Compromise of 1850, California became a free state and September 9 a state holiday.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] During the American Civil War (1861–1865), California sent gold shipments eastward to Washington in support of the Union.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] However, due to the existence of a large contingent of pro-South sympathizers within the state, the state was not able to muster any full military regiments to send eastwards to officially serve in the Union war effort.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Still, several smaller military units within the Union army, such as the "California 100 Company", were unofficially associated with the state of California due to a majority of their members being from California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] At the time of California's admission into the Union, travel between California and the rest of the continental U.S. had been a time-consuming and dangerous feat.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Nineteen years later, and seven years after it was greenlighted by President Lincoln, the first transcontinental railroad was completed in 1869.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] California was then reachable from the eastern States in a week's time.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Much of the state was well suited to fruit cultivation and agriculture in general.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Vast expanses of wheat, other cereal crops, vegetable crops, cotton, and nut and fruit trees were grown (including oranges in Southern California), and the foundation was laid for the state's prodigious agricultural production in the Central Valley and elsewhere.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] In the nineteenth century, a large number of migrants from China traveled to the state as part of the gold rush or to seek work.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Under earlier Spanish and Mexican rule, California's original native population had precipitously declined, above all, from Eurasian diseases to which the Indigenous people of California had not yet developed a natural immunity.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Under its new American administration, California's first governor Peter Hardeman Burnett instituted policies that have been described as a state-sanctioned policy of elimination of California's indigenous people.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Burnett announced in 1851 in his Second Annual Message to the Legislature: "That a war of extermination will continue to be waged between the races until the Indian race becomes extinct must be expected.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] As in other American states, indigenous peoples were forcibly removed from their lands by American settlers, like miners, ranchers, and farmers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Although California had entered the American union as a free state, the "loitering or orphaned Indians", were *de facto* enslaved by their new Anglo-American masters under the 1850 *Act for the Government and Protection of Indians*.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] One of these *de facto* slave auctions was approved by the Los Angeles City Council and occurred for nearly twenty years.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] There were many massacres in which hundreds of indigenous people were killed by settlers for their land.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Between 1850 and 1860, the California state government paid around 1.5 million dollars (some 250,000 of which was reimbursed by the federal government) to hire militias with the stated purpose of protecting settlers, however these militias perpetrated numerous massacres of indigenous people.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Indigenous people were also forcibly moved to reservations and rancherias, which were often small and isolated and without enough natural resources or funding from the government to adequately sustain the populations living on them.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] As a result, settler colonialism was a calamity for indigenous people.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Several scholars and Native American activists, including Benjamin Madley and Ed Castillo, have described the actions of the California government as a genocide, as well as the 40th governor of California Gavin Newsom.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Benjamin Madley estimates that from 1846 to 1873, between 9,492 and 16,092 indigenous people were killed, including between 1,680 and 3,741 killed by the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] In the 20th century, thousands of Japanese people migrated to California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The state in 1913 passed the Alien Land Act, excluding Asian immigrants from owning land.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] During World War II, Japanese Americans in California were interned in concentration camps; in 2020, California apologized.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Migration to California accelerated during the early 20th century with the completion of transcontinental highways like the Route 66.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] From 1900 to 1965, the population grew from fewer than one million to the greatest in the Union.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Census Bureau reported California's population as 6% Hispanic, 2.4% Asian, and 90% non-Hispanic white.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] To meet the population's needs, engineering feats like the California and Los Angeles Aqueducts; the Oroville and Shasta Dams; and the Bay and Golden Gate Bridges were built.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The state government adopted the California Master Plan for Higher Education in 1960 to develop an efficient system of public education.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Meanwhile, attracted to the mild Mediterranean climate, cheap land, and the state's variety of geography, filmmakers established the studio system in Hollywood in the 1920s.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] California manufactured 9% of U.S. armaments produced during World War II, ranking third behind New York and Michigan.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] California easily ranked first in production of military ships at drydock facilities in San Diego, Los Angeles, and the San Francisco Bay Area.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Due to the hiring opportunities California offered during the conflict, the population multiplied from the immigration it received due to the work in its war factories, military bases, and training facilities.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] After World War II, California's economy expanded due to strong aerospace and defense industries, whose size decreased following the end of the Cold War.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Stanford University began encouraging faculty and graduates to stay instead of leaving the state, and develop a high-tech region, now known as Silicon Valley.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] As a result of this, California is a world center of the entertainment and music industries, of technology, engineering, and the aerospace industry, and as the U.S. center of agricultural production.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Just before the Dot Com Bust, California had the fifth-largest economy in the world.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] In the mid and late twentieth century, race-related incidents occurred.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Tensions between police and African Americans, combined with unemployment and poverty in inner cities, led to riots, such as the 1992 Rodney King riots.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] California was the hub of the Black Panther Party, known for arming African Americans to defend against racial injustice.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Mexican, Filipino, and other migrant farm workers rallied in the state around Cesar Chavez for better pay in the 1960s and 70s.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] During the 20th century, two great disasters happened: the 1906 San Francisco earthquake and 1928 St.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Francis Dam flood remain the deadliest in U.S. history.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Although air pollution has been reduced, health problems associated with pollution continue.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Brown haze known as "smog" has been substantially abated after federal and state restrictions on automobile exhaust.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] An energy crisis in 2001 led to rolling blackouts, soaring power rates, and the importation of electricity from neighboring states.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Southern California Edison and Pacific Gas and Electric Company came under heavy criticism.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Housing prices in urban areas continued to increase; a modest home which in the 1960s cost $25,000 would cost half a million dollars or more in urban areas by 2005.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] More people commuted longer hours to afford a home in more rural areas while earning larger salaries in the urban areas.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Speculators bought houses, expecting to make a huge profit in months, then rolling it over by buying more properties.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Mortgage companies were compliant, as people assumed prices would keep rising.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The bubble burst in 2007–2008 as prices began to crash.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Hundreds of billions in property values vanished and foreclosures soared, as financial institutions and investors were badly hurt.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] In the 21st century, droughts and frequent wildfires attributed to climate change have occurred.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] From 2011 to 2017, a persistent drought was the worst in its recorded history.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] The 2018 wildfire season was the state's deadliest and most destructive.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] One of the first confirmed COVID-19 cases in the U.S. occurred in California on January 26, 2020.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] A state of emergency was declared in the state on March 4, 2020, and remained in effect until Governor Gavin Newsom ended it in February 2023.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] A mandatory statewide stay-at-home order was issued on March 19, 2020, which was ended in January 2021.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Cultural and language revitalization efforts among indigenous Californians have progressed among tribes as of 2022.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] Some land returns to indigenous stewardship have occurred.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p01] In 2022, the largest dam removal and river restoration project in U.S. history was announced for the Klamath River, as a win for California tribes.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Covering an area of 163,696 sq mi (423,970 km2), California is the third-largest state in the U.S. in area, after Alaska and Texas.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] California is one of the most geographically diverse states in the union and is often geographically bisected into two regions, Southern California, comprising the ten southernmost counties, and Northern California, comprising the 48 northernmost counties.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] In the middle of the state lies the California Central Valley, bounded by the Sierra Nevada in the east, the coastal mountain ranges in the west, the Cascade Range to the north and by the Tehachapi Mountains in the south.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The Central Valley is California's productive agricultural heartland.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Divided in two by the Sacramento-San Joaquin River Delta, the northern portion, the Sacramento Valley serves as the watershed of the Sacramento River, while the southern portion, the San Joaquin Valley is the watershed for the San Joaquin River.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Both valleys derive their names from the rivers that flow through them.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] With dredging, the Sacramento and the San Joaquin Rivers have remained deep enough for several inland cities to be seaports.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The Sacramento-San Joaquin River Delta is a critical water supply hub for the state.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Water is diverted from the delta and through an extensive network of pumps and canals that traverse nearly the length of the state, to the Central Valley and the State Water Projects and other needs.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Water from the Delta provides drinking water for nearly 23 million people, almost two-thirds of the state's population as well as water for farmers on the west side of the San Joaquin Valley.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Suisun Bay lies at the confluence of the Sacramento and San Joaquin Rivers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The water is drained by the Carquinez Strait, which flows into San Pablo Bay, a northern extension of San Francisco Bay, which then connects to the Pacific Ocean via the Golden Gate strait.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The Channel Islands are located off the Southern coast, while the Farallon Islands lie west of San Francisco.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The Sierra Nevada (Spanish for "snowy range") includes the highest peak in the contiguous 48 states, Mount Whitney, at 14,505 feet (4,421 m).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The range embraces Yosemite Valley, famous for its glacially carved domes, and Sequoia National Park, home to the giant sequoia trees, the largest living organisms on Earth, and the deep freshwater lake, Lake Tahoe, the largest lake in the state by volume.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] To the east of the Sierra Nevada are Owens Valley and Mono Lake, an essential migratory bird habitat.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] In the western part of the state is Clear Lake, the largest freshwater lake by area entirely in California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Although Lake Tahoe is larger, it is divided by the California/Nevada border.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The Sierra Nevada falls to Arctic temperatures in winter and has several dozen small glaciers, including Palisade Glacier, the southernmost glacier in the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The Tulare Lake was the largest freshwater lake west of the Mississippi River.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] A remnant of Pleistocene-era Lake Corcoran, Tulare Lake dried up by the early 20th century after its tributary rivers were diverted for agricultural irrigation and municipal water uses.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] About 45% of the state's total surface area is covered by forests, and California's diversity of pine species is unmatched by any other state.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] California contains more forestland than any other state except Alaska.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Many of the trees in the California White Mountains are the oldest in the world; an individual bristlecone pine is over 5,000 years old.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] In the south is a large inland salt lake, the Salton Sea.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The south-central desert is called the Mojave; to the northeast of the Mojave lies Death Valley, which contains the lowest and hottest place in North America, the Badwater Basin at −279 feet (−85 m).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The horizontal distance from the bottom of Death Valley to the top of Mount Whitney is less than 90 miles (140 km).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Indeed, almost all of southeastern California is arid, hot desert, with routine extreme high temperatures during the summer.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The southeastern border of California with Arizona is entirely formed by the Colorado River, from which the southern part of the state gets about half of its water.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] A majority of California's cities are located in either the San Francisco Bay Area or the Sacramento metropolitan area in Northern California; or the Los Angeles area, the Inland Empire, or the San Diego metropolitan area in Southern California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The Los Angeles Area, the Bay Area, and the San Diego metropolitan area are among several major metropolitan areas along the California coast.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] As part of the Ring of Fire, California is subject to tsunamis, floods, droughts, Santa Ana winds, wildfires, and landslides on steep terrain; California also has several volcanoes.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] It has many earthquakes due to several faults running through the state, the largest being the San Andreas Fault.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] About 37,000 earthquakes are recorded each year; most are too small to be felt.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Among Americans at risk of serious harm from a major earthquake, two-thirds of that population are residents of California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Most of the state has a Mediterranean climate.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The cool California Current offshore often creates summer fog near the coast.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Farther inland, there are colder winters and hotter summers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The maritime moderation results in the shoreline summertime temperatures of Los Angeles and San Francisco being the coolest of all major metropolitan areas of the U.S. and uniquely cool compared to areas on the same latitude in the interior and on the east coast of the North American continent.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Even the San Diego shoreline bordering Mexico is cooler in summer than most areas in the contiguous U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Just a few miles inland, summer temperature extremes are significantly higher, with downtown Los Angeles being several degrees warmer than at the coast.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The same microclimate phenomenon is seen in the climate of the Bay Area, where areas sheltered from the ocean experience significantly hotter summers and colder winters in contrast with nearby areas closer to the ocean.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Northern parts of the state have more rain than the south.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] California's mountain ranges also influence the climate: some of the rainiest parts of the state are west-facing mountain slopes.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Coastal northwestern California has a temperate climate, and the Central Valley has a Mediterranean climate but with greater temperature extremes than the coast.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The high mountains, including the Sierra Nevada, have an alpine climate with snow in winter and mild to moderate heat in summer.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] California's mountains produce rain shadows on the eastern side, creating extensive deserts.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The higher elevation deserts of eastern California have hot summers and cold winters, while the low deserts east of the Southern California mountains have hot summers and nearly frostless mild winters.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Death Valley, a desert with large expanses below sea level, is considered the hottest location in the world; the highest temperature in the world, 134 °F (56.7 °C), was recorded there on July 10, 1913.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The lowest temperature in California was −45 °F (−43 °C) on January 20, 1937, in Boca.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The table below lists average temperatures for January and August in a selection of places throughout the state; some highly populated and some not.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] This includes the relatively cool summers of the Humboldt Bay region around Eureka, the extreme heat of Death Valley, and the mountain climate of Mammoth in the Sierra Nevada.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The wide range of climates leads to a high demand for water.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Over time, droughts have been increasing due to climate change and overextraction, becoming less seasonal and more year-round, further straining California's electricity supply and water security and having an impact on California business, industry, and agriculture.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] In 2022, a new state program was created in collaboration with indigenous peoples of California to revive the practice of controlled burns as a way of clearing excessive forest debris and making landscapes more resilient to wildfires.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Native American use of fire in ecosystem management was outlawed in 1911, yet has now been recognized.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] California is one of the ecologically richest and most diverse parts of the world, and includes some of the most endangered ecological communities.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] California is part of the Nearctic realm and spans a number of terrestrial ecoregions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] California's large number of endemic species includes relict species, which have died out elsewhere, such as the Catalina ironwood (*Lyonothamnus floribundus*).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Many other endemics originated through differentiation or adaptive radiation, whereby multiple species develop from a common ancestor to take advantage of diverse ecological conditions such as the California lilac (*Ceanothus*).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Many California endemics have become endangered, as urbanization, logging, overgrazing, and the introduction of exotic species have encroached on their habitat.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] California boasts several superlatives in its collection of flora: the largest trees, the tallest trees, and the oldest trees.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] California's native grasses are perennial plants, and there are close to hundred succulent species native to the state.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] After European contact, these were generally replaced by invasive species of European annual grasses; and, in modern times, California's hills turn a characteristic golden-brown in summer.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Plant life in the dry climate of the lower Sonoran zone contains a diversity of native cactus, mesquite, and paloverde.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The Joshua tree is found in the Mojave Desert.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Flowering plants include the dwarf desert poppy and a variety of asters.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Fremont cottonwood and valley oak thrive in the Central Valley.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The upper Sonoran zone includes the chaparral belt, characterized by forests of small shrubs, stunted trees, and herbaceous plants.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] *Nemophila*, mint, *Phacelia*, *Viola*, and the California poppy (*Eschscholzia californica*, the state flower) also flourish in this zone, along with the lupine, more species of which occur here than anywhere else in the world.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The transition zone includes most of California's forests with the redwood (*Sequoia sempervirens*) and the "big tree" or giant sequoia (*Sequoiadendron giganteum*), among the oldest living things on earth (some are said to have lived at least 4,000 years).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Tanbark oak, California laurel, sugar pine, madrona, broad-leaved maple, and Douglas-fir also grow here.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Forest floors are covered with swordfern, alumnroot, barrenwort, and trillium, and there are thickets of huckleberry, azalea, elder, and wild currant.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Characteristic wild flowers include varieties of mariposa, tulip, and tiger and leopard lilies.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The high elevations of the Canadian zone allow the Jeffrey pine, red fir, and lodgepole pine to thrive.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Brushy areas are abundant with dwarf manzanita and ceanothus; the unique Sierra puffball is also found here.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Right below the timberline, in the Hudsonian zone, the whitebark, foxtail, and silver pines grow.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] At about 10,500 feet (3,200 m), begins the Arctic zone, a treeless region whose flora include a number of wildflowers, including Sierra primrose, yellow columbine, alpine buttercup, and alpine shooting star.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Palm trees are a well-known feature of California, particularly in Southern California and Los Angeles; many species have been imported, though the *Washington filifera* (commonly known as the *California fan palm*) is native to the state, mainly growing in the Colorado Desert oases.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Other common plants that have been introduced to the state include the eucalyptus, acacia, pepper tree, geranium, and Scotch broom.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The species that are federally classified as endangered are the Contra Costa wallflower, Antioch Dunes evening primrose, Solano grass, San Clemente Island larkspur, salt marsh bird's beak, McDonald's rock-cress, and Santa Barbara Island liveforever.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] As of December 1997, 85 plant species were listed as threatened or endangered.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] In the deserts of the lower Sonoran zone, the mammals include the jackrabbit, kangaroo rat, squirrel, and opossum.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Common birds include the owl, roadrunner, cactus wren, and various species of hawk.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The area's reptilian life include the sidewinder viper, desert tortoise, and horned toad.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The upper Sonoran zone boasts mammals such as the antelope, brown-footed woodrat, and ring-tailed cat.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Birds unique to this zone are the California thrasher, bushtit, and California condor.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] In the transition zone, there are Colombian black-tailed deer, black bears, gray foxes, cougars, bobcats, and Roosevelt elk.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Reptiles such as the garter snakes and rattlesnakes inhabit the zone.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] In addition, amphibians such as the water puppy and redwood salamander are common too.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Birds such as the kingfisher, chickadee, towhee, and hummingbird thrive here as well.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The Canadian zone mammals include the mountain weasel, snowshoe hare, and several species of chipmunks.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Conspicuous birds include the blue-fronted jay, mountain chickadee, hermit thrush, American dipper, and Townsend's solitaire.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] As one ascends into the Hudsonian zone, birds become scarcer.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] While the gray-crowned rosy finch is the only bird native to the high Arctic region, other bird species such as Anna's hummingbird and Clark's nutcracker.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Principal mammals found in this region include the Sierra coney, white-tailed jackrabbit, and the bighorn sheep.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] As of April 2003, the bighorn sheep was listed as endangered by the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The fauna found throughout several zones are the mule deer, coyote, mountain lion, northern flicker, and several species of hawk and sparrow.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Aquatic life in California thrives, from the state's mountain lakes and streams to the rocky Pacific coastline.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Numerous trout species are found, among them rainbow, golden, and cutthroat.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Migratory species of salmon are common as well.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Deep-sea life forms include sea bass, yellowfin tuna, barracuda, and several types of whale.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Native to the cliffs of northern California are seals, sea lions, and many types of shorebirds, including migratory species.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] As of April 2003, 118 California animals were on the federal endangered list; 181 plants were listed as endangered or threatened.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Eleven butterflies are also endangered and two that are threatened are on the federal list.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Among threatened animals are the coastal California gnatcatcher, Paiute cutthroat trout, southern sea otter, and northern spotted owl.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] California has a total of 290,821 acres (1,176.91 km2) of National Wildlife Refuges.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] As of September 2010, 123 California animals were listed as either endangered or threatened on the federal list.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Also, as of the same year, 178 species of California plants were listed either as endangered or threatened on this federal list.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The most prominent river system within California is formed by the Sacramento River and San Joaquin River, which are fed mostly by snowmelt from the west slope of the Sierra Nevada, and respectively drain the north and south halves of the Central Valley.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The two rivers join in the Sacramento–San Joaquin River Delta, flowing into the Pacific Ocean through San Francisco Bay.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Many major tributaries feed into the Sacramento–San Joaquin system, including the Pit River, Feather River and Tuolumne River.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The Klamath and Trinity Rivers drain a large area in far northwestern California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The Eel River and Salinas River each drain portions of the California coast, north and south of San Francisco Bay, respectively.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The Mojave River is the primary watercourse in the Mojave Desert, and the Santa Ana River drains much of the Transverse Ranges as it bisects Southern California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The Colorado River forms the state's southeast border with Arizona.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Most of California's major rivers are dammed as part of two massive water projects: the Central Valley Project, providing water for agriculture in the Central Valley, and the California State Water Project diverting water from Northern to Southern California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The state's coasts, rivers, and other bodies of water are regulated by the California Coastal Commission.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] California is traditionally separated into Northern California and Southern California, divided by a straight border which runs across the state, separating the northern 48 counties from the southern 10 counties.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Despite the persistence of the northern-southern divide, California is more precisely divided into many regions, multiple of which stretch across the northern-southern divide.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The state has 483 incorporated cities and towns, of which 461 are cities and 22 are towns.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Under California law, the terms "city" and "town" are explicitly interchangeable; the name of an incorporated municipality in the state can either be "City of (Name)" or "Town of (Name)".
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Sacramento became California's first incorporated city on February 27, 1850.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] San Jose, San Diego, and Benicia tied for California's second incorporated city, each receiving incorporation on March 27, 1850.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Mountain House became the state's most recent and 483rd incorporated municipality on July 1, 2024.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The majority of these cities and towns are within one of five metropolitan areas: the Los Angeles Metropolitan Area, the San Francisco Bay Area, the Riverside-San Bernardino Area, the San Diego metropolitan area, or the Sacramento metropolitan area.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Presently, close to one out of every nine U.S. residents live in California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] According to the 2020 U.S. census, the population of California was 39.54 million on April 1, 2020, a 6.13% increase since 2010.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] During that decade, the state's population grew more slowly than the rest of the nation, resulting in the loss of one seat on the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] House of Representatives, the first loss in its entire history.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The estimated state population in 2023 was 38.94 million.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] For well over a century (1900–2020), California experienced steady population growth.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Even while the rate of growth began to slow by the 1990s, some growth progressed into the first two decades of the 21st century; California added an average of around 400,000 people per year to its population during the period 1940–2020.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Then in 2020, the state began to experience population declines continuing every year, attributable mostly to moves out of state but also due to declining birth rates, COVID-19 pandemic deaths, and less internal migration from other states to California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Census Bureau, between 2021 and 2022, 818,000 California residents moved out of state with emigrants listing high cost of living, California housing shortage rise of remote work, high taxes, and a difficult business environment as the motivation.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The net loss of population in California between July 2020 and July 2023 was 433,000.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] As of the 2020 Census, California had a population density of 250/mi2 and a population-weighted density of 7954/mi2.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The Greater Los Angeles Area is the second-largest metropolitan area in the U.S., while Los Angeles is the second-largest city in the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Los Angeles County has held the title of most populous U.S. county for decades and it alone is more populous than 42 U.S. states.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] San Francisco is the most densely populated city in California and one of the most densely populated cities in the U.S..
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Four of the top 20 most populous cities in the U.S. are in California: Los Angeles (2nd), San Diego (8th), San Jose (13th), and San Francisco (17th).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The center of population of California is located four miles west-southwest of the city of Shafter, Kern County.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] As of 2020, California ranked fourth among states by life expectancy, with a life expectancy of 79.0 years.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Starting in 2010, for the first time since the California Gold Rush, California-born residents made up the majority of the state's population.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Along with the rest of the U.S., California's immigration pattern has also shifted over the course of the late 2000s to early 2010s.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Immigration from Latin American countries has dropped significantly with most immigrants now coming from Asia.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] In total for 2011, there were 277,304 immigrants; 57% came from Asian countries versus 22% from Latin American countries.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Net immigration from Mexico, previously the most common country of origin for new immigrants, has dropped to zero / less than zero since more Mexican nationals are departing for their home country than immigrating.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The state's population of undocumented immigrants has been shrinking in recent years, due to increased enforcement and decreased job opportunities for lower-skilled workers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The number of migrants arrested attempting to cross the Mexican border in the Southwest decreased from a high of 1.1 million in 2005 to 367,000 in 2011.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Despite these recent trends, undocumented immigrants constituted an estimated 7.3% of the state's population, the third highest percentage of any state in the country, totaling nearly 2.6 million.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] In particular, illegal immigrants tended to be concentrated in Los Angeles, Monterey, San Benito, Imperial, and Napa Counties—the latter four of which have significant agricultural industries that depend on manual labor.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] More than half of illegal immigrants originate from Mexico.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The state of California and some California cities, including Los Angeles, Oakland, and San Francisco, have adopted sanctuary policies.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] According to HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 171,521 homeless people in California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] These numbers add up to more than 100% because respondents can select multiple racial identities.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] 19% of Californians identified as two or more races in 2022, although excluding respondents who selected "some other race", only 5% identified as two or more races.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] By ethnicity, in 2018 the population was 60.7% non-Hispanic (of any race) and 39.3% Hispanic or Latino (of any race).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Hispanics are the largest single ethnic group in California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Non-Hispanic whites constituted 36.8% of the state's population.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] *Californios* are the Hispanic residents native to California, who make up the Spanish-speaking community that has existed in California since 1542, of varying Mexican American/Chicano, Criollo Spaniard, and Mestizo origin.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] However, they make up only a small part of California's Hispanic population today, estimated at 500,000.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] California has the largest Mexican, Salvadoran, and Guatemalan populations in the U.S., together making up over 90% of the state's Latino population.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] As of 2011, 75.1% of California's population younger than age 1 were minorities, meaning they had at least one parent who was not non-Hispanic white (white Hispanics are counted as minorities).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] In terms of total numbers, California has the largest population of White Americans in the U.S., an estimated 22,200,000 residents including people identifying as white in combination with any other race.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The state has the 5th largest population of African Americans in the U.S., an estimated 2,250,000 residents.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] California's Asian American population is estimated at 7.1 million, constituting a third of the nation's total.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] California's Native American population of 504,000 is the most of any state, with 103,030 identifying as Non-Hispanic and belonging mostly to the Indigenous peoples of California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Most of the state's Native American population identifies as Hispanic and belongs to Indigenous Mexican or Central American ethnic groups, including 185,200 identifying as Mexican American Indian and 67,904 identifying as Central American Indian.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] According to estimates from 2011, California has the largest minority population in the U.S. by numbers, making up 60% of the state population.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Over the past 25 years, the population of non-Hispanic whites has declined, while Hispanic and Asian populations have grown.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Between 1970 and 2011, non-Hispanic whites declined from 80% of the state's population to 40%, while Hispanics grew from 32% in 2000 to 38% in 2011.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] It is currently projected that Hispanics will rise to 49% of the population by 2060, primarily due to domestic births rather than immigration.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] With the decline of immigration from Latin America, Asian Americans now constitute the fastest growing racial/ethnic group in California; this growth is primarily driven by immigration from China, India, and the Philippines, respectively.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The majority of California's immigrants were born in Latin America (49%) or Asia (41%).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] English serves as California's de jure and de facto official language.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] According to the 2021 American Community Survey conducted by the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Census Bureau, 56.08% (20,763,638) of California residents age 5 and older spoke only English at home, while 43.92% spoke another language at home.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Some 60.35% of California residents who speak a language other than English at home are able to speak English "well" or "very well", with this figure varying significantly across the different linguistic groups.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Like most U.S. states (32 out of 50), California law enshrines English as its official language, and has done so since the passage of Proposition 63 by California voters in 1986.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Various government agencies do, and are often required to, furnish documents in the various languages needed to reach their intended audiences.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Spanish is the most commonly spoken language in California behind English, spoken by 28.18% (10,434,308) of the state's population in 2021.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The Spanish language has been spoken in California since 1542 and is deeply intertwined with California's cultural landscape and history.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Spanish was the official administrative language of California through the Spanish and Mexican eras, until 1848.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Conquest of California and the Treaty of Guadalupe-Hidalgo, the U.S. federal government guaranteed the rights of Spanish-speaking Californians.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The first Constitution of California was written in both languages at the Monterey Constitutional Convention of 1849 and protected the rights of Spanish speakers to use their language in government proceedings and mandating that all government documents be published in both English and Spanish.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Despite the initial recognition of Spanish by early American governments in California, the revised 1879 state constitution stripped the rights of Spanish speakers and the official status of Spanish.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The growth of the English-only movement by the mid-20th century led to the passage of 1986 California Proposition 63, which enshrined English as the only official language in California and ended Spanish as a language of instruction in public schools.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] 2016 California Proposition 58 reversed the prohibition on bilingual education, though there are still many barriers to the proliferation of Spanish bilingual education, including a shortage of teachers and lack of funding.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The government of California has since made efforts to promote Spanish language access and bilingual education, as have private educational institutions in California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Many businesses in California promote Spanish language skills for their employees, to better serve both California's Hispanic population and the larger Spanish-speaking world.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] California has historically been one of the most linguistically diverse areas in the world, with more than 70 indigenous languages derived from 64 root languages in six language families.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] A survey conducted between 2007 and 2009 identified 23 different indigenous languages among California farmworkers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] All of California's indigenous languages are endangered, although there are now efforts toward language revitalization.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] California has the highest concentration nationwide of Chinese, Vietnamese and Punjabi speakers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] As a result of the state's increasing diversity and migration from other areas across the country and around the globe, linguists began noticing a noteworthy set of emerging characteristics of spoken American English in California since the late 20th century.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] This variety, known as California English, has a vowel shift and several other phonological processes that are different from varieties of American English used in other regions of the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The largest religious denominations by number of adherents as a percentage of California's population in 2014 were the Catholic Church with 28%, Evangelical Protestants with 20%, and Mainline Protestants with 10%.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Together, all kinds of Protestants accounted for 32%.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] Those unaffiliated with any religion represented 27% of the population.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The breakdown of other religions is 1% Muslim, 2% Hindu and 2% Buddhist.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] This is a change from 2008, when the population identified their religion with the Catholic Church with 31%; Evangelical Protestants with 18%; and Mainline Protestants with 14%.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] In 2008, those unaffiliated with any religion represented 21% of the population.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The breakdown of other religions in 2008 was 0.5% Muslim, 1% Hindu and 2% Buddhist.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The *American Jewish Year Book* placed the total Jewish population of California at about 1,194,190 in 2006.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] According to the Association of Religion Data Archives (ARDA) the largest denominations by adherents in 2010 were the Catholic Church with 10,233,334; The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints with 763,818; and the Southern Baptist Convention with 489,953.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] California has a large Catholic population due to the large numbers of Mexicans and Central Americans living within its borders.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] California has twelve dioceses and two archdioceses, the Archdiocese of Los Angeles and the Archdiocese of San Francisco, the former being the largest archdiocese in the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] A Pew Research Center survey revealed that California is somewhat less religious than the rest of the states: 62% of Californians say they are "absolutely certain" of their belief in God, while in the nation 71% say so.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p02] The survey also revealed 48% of Californians say religion is "very important", compared to 56% nationally.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The culture of California is a Western culture and has its modern roots in U.S. culture, but also, historically, many Hispanic Californio and Mexican influences.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] As a border and coastal state, California culture has been greatly influenced by several large immigrant populations, especially those from Latin America and Asia.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California has long been a subject of interest in the public mind and has often been promoted by its boosters as a kind of paradise.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In the early 20th century, fueled by the efforts of state, the building projects during the Great Depression and local boosters, many Americans saw the Golden State as an ideal resort destination, sunny and dry all year round with easy access to the ocean and mountains.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In the 1960s, popular music groups such as the Beach Boys promoted the image of Californians as laid-back, tanned beach-goers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Hollywood and the rest of the Los Angeles area is a major global center for entertainment, with the U.S. film industry's "Big Five" major film studios (Columbia, Disney, Paramount, Universal, and Warner Bros.) as well as many minor film studios being based in or around the area.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Many animation studios are also headquartered in the state.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The four major American television commercial broadcast networks (ABC, CBS, NBC, and Fox) as well as other networks all have production facilities and offices in the state.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] All the four major commercial broadcast networks, plus the two major Spanish-language networks (Telemundo and Univision) each have at least three owned-and-operated TV stations in California, including at least one in Los Angeles and at least one in San Francisco.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] One of the oldest radio stations in the U.S. still in existence, KCBS (AM) in the San Francisco Bay Area, was founded in 1909.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Universal Music Group, one of the "Big Four" record labels, is based in Santa Monica, while Warner Records is based in Los Angeles.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Many independent record labels, such as Mind of a Genius Records, are also headquartered in the state.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Other genres such as pop rock, indie rock, hard rock, hip hop, pop, rock, rockabilly, country, heavy metal, grunge, new wave and disco were popularized in the state.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In addition, many British bands, such as Led Zeppelin, Deep Purple, Black Sabbath, and the Rolling Stones settled in the state after becoming internationally famous.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] As the home of Silicon Valley, the Bay Area is the headquarters of several prominent internet media, social media, and other technology companies.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Three of the "Big Five" technology companies (Apple, Meta, and Google) are based in the area as well as other services such as Netflix, Pandora Radio, Twitter, Yahoo!, and YouTube.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Other prominent companies that are headquartered here include HP inc. and Intel.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Microsoft and Amazon also have offices in the area.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California, particularly Southern California, is considered the birthplace of modern car culture.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Several fast food, fast casual, and casual dining chains were also founded California, including some that have since expanded internationally like California Pizza Kitchen, Denny's, IHOP, McDonald's, Panda Express, and Taco Bell.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California has 18 major professional sports league franchises, far more than any other state.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The San Francisco Bay Area has five major league teams, while the Greater Los Angeles Area is home to ten.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] San Diego has two major league teams and Sacramento has one.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The NFL Super Bowl has been hosted in California 12 times at five different stadiums: Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum, the Rose Bowl, Stanford Stadium, Levi's Stadium, and San Diego Stadium.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] A thirteenth, Super Bowl LVI, was held at SoFi Stadium in Inglewood on February 13, 2022.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California has long had many respected collegiate sports programs.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California is home to the oldest college bowl game, the annual Rose Bowl, among others.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The NFL has three teams in the state: the Los Angeles Rams, Los Angeles Chargers, and San Francisco 49ers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] MLB has four teams in the state: the San Francisco Giants, Los Angeles Dodgers, Los Angeles Angels, and San Diego Padres.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The NBA has four teams in the state: the Golden State Warriors, Los Angeles Clippers, Los Angeles Lakers, and Sacramento Kings.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Additionally, the WNBA also has two teams in the state: the Los Angeles Sparks and Golden State Valkyries.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The NHL has three teams in the state: the Anaheim Ducks, Los Angeles Kings, and San Jose Sharks.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] MLS has four teams in the state: the Los Angeles Galaxy, San Jose Earthquakes, Los Angeles FC, and San Diego FC.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] MLR has one team in the state: the San Diego Legion.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California is the only U.S. state to have hosted both the Summer and Winter Olympics.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The 1932 and 1984 summer games were held in Los Angeles.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Squaw Valley Ski Resort (now Palisades Tahoe) in the Lake Tahoe region hosted the 1960 Winter Olympics.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Los Angeles will host the 2028 Summer Olympics, marking the fourth time that California will have hosted the Olympic Games.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Multiple games during the 1994 FIFA World Cup took place in California, with the Rose Bowl hosting eight matches (including the final), while Stanford Stadium hosted six matches.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The 2026 World Cup is scheduled to return in 2026, from June 11 to July 19.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] SoFi Stadium in Los Angeles will host eight matches, including three group stage fixtures, two Round of 32 clashes, and a highly anticipated Quarter-Final.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In addition to the Olympic games, California also hosts the California State Games.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Many sports, such as surfing, snowboarding, and skateboarding, were invented in California, while others like volleyball, beach soccer, and skiing were popularized in the state.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Other sports that are big in the state include golf, rodeo, tennis, mountain climbing, marathon running, horse racing, bowling, mixed martial arts, boxing, and motorsports, especially NASCAR and Formula One.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California has the most school students in the country, with over 6.2 million in the 2005–06 school year, giving California more students in school than 36 states have in total population and one of the highest projected enrollments in the country.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Public secondary education consists of high schools that teach elective courses in trades, languages, and liberal arts with tracks for gifted, college-bound and industrial arts students.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California's public educational system is supported by a unique constitutional amendment that requires a minimum annual funding level for grades K–12 and community colleges that grows with the economy and student enrollment figures.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In 2016, California's K–12 public school per-pupil spending was ranked 22nd in the nation ($11,500 per student vs. $11,800 for the U.S. average).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] For 2012, California's K–12 public schools ranked 48th in the number of employees per student, at 0.102 (the U.S. average was 0.137), while paying the 7th most per employee, $49,000 (the U.S. average was $39,000).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] , and the state's flagship public university.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] is a private university that is one of the top-ranked universities in the world.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California has a particularly high density of arts colleges, including the California College of the Arts, California Institute of the Arts, San Francisco Art Institute, Art Center College of Design, and Academy of Art University, among others.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Bureau of Economic Analysis, in 2025, California's gross state product (GSP) was $4.250 trillion, the largest of any U.S. state and the state's per capita personal income was $91,116.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California is responsible for one seventh of the nation's gross domestic product (GDP).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] As of 2025, California's nominal GDP is larger than all but four countries.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In terms of purchasing power parity (PPP), it is larger than all but eight countries.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California's economy is larger than Africa's and Australia's and is almost as large as South America's.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The state recorded total, non-farm employment of 16,677,800 as of September 2021 among 966,224 employer establishments.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] As of 2024, California is home to 57 of the *Fortune* 500 companies, the highest number of any U.S. state.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In 2025, 465,101 businesses formed in California, the second highest in the country behind Florida.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] As of 2025, 4.3 million small businesses were in the state, making up 99.8% of businesses, and employing 47.4% of the state's work force.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] As the largest and second-largest U.S. ports respectively, the Port of Los Angeles and the Port of Long Beach in Southern California collectively play a pivotal role in the global supply chain, together hauling in about 40% of all imports to the U.S. by TEU volume.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The Port of Oakland and Port of Hueneme are the 10th and 26th largest seaports in the U.S., respectively, by number of TEUs handled.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The five largest sectors of employment in California are trade, transportation, and utilities; government; professional and business services; education and health services; and leisure and hospitality.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In output, the five largest sectors are financial services, followed by trade, transportation, and utilities; education and health services; government; and manufacturing.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California has an unemployment rate of 5.3% as of May 2025.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California's economy is dependent on trade and international related commerce accounts for about one-quarter of the state's economy, and representing 7% of their GDP; California's biggest trade partner is Mexico.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In 2008, California exported $144 billion worth of goods, up from $134 billion in 2007 and $127 billion in 2006.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Vehicles, computers and electronic products are California's top exports, accounting for 42% of all the state's exports in 2008; over 50 car companies operate in California, such as Tesla and Mazda.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Agriculture is an important sector in California's economy.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Department of Agriculture, in 2011, the three largest California agricultural products by value were milk and cream, shelled almonds, and grapes.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Farming-related sales more than quadrupled over the past three decades, from $7.3 billion in 1974 to nearly $31 billion in 2004.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] This increase has occurred despite a 15% decline in acreage devoted to farming during the period, and water supply suffering from chronic instability.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Factors contributing to the growth in sales-per-acre include more intensive use of active farmlands and technological improvements in crop production.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In 2008, California's 81,500 farms and ranches generated $36.2 billion products revenue.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In 2011, that number grew to $43.5 billion products revenue.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The agriculture sector accounts for 2% of the state's GDP and employs around 3% of its total workforce.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Per capita GDP in 2021 was $85,546, ranking fourth in the nation.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Per capita income varies widely by geographic region and profession.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The Central Valley is the most impoverished, with migrant farm workers making less than minimum wage.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] According to a 2005 report by the Congressional Research Service, the San Joaquin Valley was characterized as one of the most economically depressed regions in the U.S., on par with the region of Appalachia.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Using the supplemental poverty measure, California has a poverty rate of 23.5%, the highest of any state in the country.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] However, using the official measure the poverty rate was only 13.3% as of 2017.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Many coastal cities include some of the wealthiest per-capita areas in the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The high-technology sectors in Northern California, specifically Silicon Valley, in Santa Clara and San Mateo counties, have emerged from the economic downturn caused by the dot-com bust.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In 2019, there were 1,042,027 millionaire households in the state, more than any other state in the nation.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In 2010, California residents were ranked first among the states with the best average credit score of 754.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] State spending increased from $56 billion in 1998 to $127 billion in 2011.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California has the third highest per capita spending on welfare among the states, as well as the highest spending on welfare at $6.67 billion.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In January 2011, California's total debt was at least $265 billion.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] On June 27, 2013, Governor Jerry Brown signed a balanced budget (no deficit) for the state, its first in decades; however, the state's debt remains at $132 billion.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] While Proposition 30 also enacted a minimum state sales tax of 7.5%, this sales tax increase was not extended by Proposition 55 and reverted to a previous minimum state sales tax rate of 7.25% in 2017.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Local governments can and do levy additional sales taxes in addition to this minimum rate.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Property tax increases are capped at 2% annually or the rate of inflation (whichever is lower), per Proposition 13.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Because it is the most populous state in the U.S., California is one of the country's largest users of energy.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The state has extensive hydro-electric energy generation facilities, however, moving water is the single largest energy use in the state.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Also, due to high energy rates, conservation mandates, mild weather in the largest population centers and strong environmental movement, its *per capita* energy use is one of the smallest of any state in the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Due to the high electricity demand, California imports more electricity than any other state, primarily hydroelectric power from states in the Pacific Northwest (via Path 15 and Path 66) and coal- and natural gas-fired production from the desert Southwest via Path 46.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The state's crude oil and natural gas deposits are located in the Central Valley and along the coast, including the large Midway-Sunset Oil Field.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Natural gas-fired power plants typically account for more than one-half of state electricity generation.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] As a result of the state's strong environmental movement, California has some of the most aggressive renewable energy goals in the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The Clean Energy, Jobs and Affordability Act of 2022 commits the state to running its operations on clean, renewable energy resources by 2035, and SB 1203 also requires the state to achieve net-zero operations for all agencies.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Currently, several solar power plants such as the Solar Energy Generating Systems facility are located in the Mojave Desert.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California's wind farms include Altamont Pass, San Gorgonio Pass, and Tehachapi Pass.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The Tehachapi area is also where the Tehachapi Energy Storage Project is located.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Several dams across the state provide hydro-electric power.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] It would be possible to convert the total supply to 100% renewable energy, including heating, cooling and mobility, by 2050.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California has one major nuclear power plant (Diablo Canyon) in operation.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The San Onofre nuclear plant was shut down in 2013.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] More than 1,700 tons of radioactive waste are stored at San Onofre, and sit on the coast where there is a record of past tsunamis.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Voters banned the approval of new nuclear power plants since the late 1970s because of concerns over radioactive waste disposal.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Several cities such as Oakland, Berkeley and Davis have declared themselves as nuclear-free zones.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California's vast terrain is connected by an extensive system of controlled-access highways ('freeways'), limited-access roads ('expressways'), and highways.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California is known for its car culture, giving California's cities a reputation for severe traffic congestion.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Construction and maintenance of state roads and statewide transportation planning are primarily the responsibility of the California Department of Transportation, nicknamed "Caltrans".
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The rapidly growing population of the state is straining all of its transportation networks, and California has some of the worst roads in the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The Reason Foundation's 19th Annual Report on the Performance of State Highway Systems ranked California's highways the third-worst of any state, with Alaska second, and Rhode Island first.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The state has been a pioneer in road construction.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] One of the state's more visible landmarks, the Golden Gate Bridge, was the longest suspension bridge main span in the world at 4,200 feet (1,300 m) between 1937 (when it opened) and 1964.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] With its orange paint and panoramic views of the bay, this highway bridge is a popular tourist attraction and also accommodates pedestrians and bicyclists.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The San Francisco–Oakland Bay Bridge (often abbreviated the "Bay Bridge"), completed in 1936, transports about 280,000 vehicles per day on two-decks.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Its two sections meet at Yerba Buena Island through the world's largest diameter transportation bore tunnel, at 76 feet (23 m) wide by 58 feet (18 m) high.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The Arroyo Seco Parkway, connecting Los Angeles and Pasadena, opened in 1940 as the first freeway in the Western U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] It was later extended south to the Four Level Interchange in downtown Los Angeles, regarded as the first stack interchange ever built.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The California Highway Patrol is the largest statewide police agency in the U.S. in employment with more than 10,000 employees.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] They are responsible for providing any police-sanctioned service to anyone on California's state-maintained highways and on state property.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Los Angeles International Airport (LAX), the 4th busiest airport in the world in 2018, and San Francisco International Airport (SFO), the 25th busiest airport in the world in 2018, are major hubs for trans-Pacific and transcontinental traffic.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] There are about a dozen important commercial airports and many more general aviation airports throughout the state.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Inter-city rail travel is provided by Amtrak California; the three routes, the *Capitol Corridor*, *Pacific Surfliner*, and *Gold Runner*, are funded by Caltrans.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] These services are the busiest intercity rail lines in the U.S. outside the Northeast Corridor and ridership is continuing to set records.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The routes are becoming increasingly popular over flying, especially on the LAX-SFO route.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Integrated subway and light rail networks are found in Los Angeles (Los Angeles Metro Rail) and San Francisco (Muni Metro).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Light rail systems are also found in San Jose (VTA light rail), San Diego (San Diego Trolley), Sacramento (SacRT light rail), and Northern San Diego County (Sprinter).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Furthermore, commuter rail networks serve the San Francisco Bay Area (Altamont Corridor Express, Bay Area Rapid Transit, Caltrain, Sonoma–Marin Area Rail Transit), Greater Los Angeles (Metrolink), and San Diego County (Coaster).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The California High-Speed Rail Authority was authorized in 1996 by the state legislature to plan a California High-Speed Rail system to put before the voters.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The plan they devised, 2008 California Proposition 1A, connecting all the major population centers in the state, was approved by the voters at the November 2008 general election.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The first phase of construction was begun in 2015, and the first segment 171 miles (275 km) long, is planned to be put into operation by the end of 2030.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Planning and work on the rest of the system is continuing, with funding for completing it is an ongoing issue.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California's 2023 integrated passenger rail master plan includes a high speed rail system.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Nearly all counties operate bus lines, and many cities operate their own city bus lines as well.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Intercity bus travel is provided by Greyhound, Megabus, and Amtrak Thruway.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California's interconnected water system is the world's largest, managing over 40,000,000 acre-feet (49 km3) of water per year, centered on six main systems of aqueducts and infrastructure projects.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Water use and conservation in California is a politically divisive issue, as the state experiences periodic droughts and has to balance the demands of its large agricultural and urban sectors, especially in the arid southern portion of the state.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The state's widespread redistribution of water also invites the frequent scorn of environmentalists.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The California Water Wars, a conflict between Los Angeles and the Owens Valley over water rights, is one of the most well-known examples of the struggle to secure adequate water supplies.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The capital city of California is Sacramento.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The state also allows ballot propositions: direct participation of the electorate by initiative, referendum, recall, and ratification.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Before the passage of Proposition 14 in 2010, California allowed each political party to choose whether to have a closed primary or a primary where only party members and independents vote.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] After June 8, 2010, when Proposition 14 was approved, excepting only the U.S. president and county central committee offices, all candidates in the primary elections are listed on the ballot with their preferred party affiliation, but they are not the official nominee of that party.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] At the primary election, the two candidates with the top votes will advance to the general election regardless of party affiliation.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] This is known as a nonpartisan blanket primary.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] If at a special primary election, one candidate receives more than 50% of all the votes cast, they are elected to fill the vacancy and no special general election will be held.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The California executive branch consists of the governor and seven other elected constitutional officers: lieutenant governor, attorney general, secretary of state, state controller, state treasurer, insurance commissioner, and state superintendent of public instruction.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] They serve four-year terms and may be re-elected only once.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The many California state agencies that are under the governor's cabinet are grouped together to form cabinet-level entities that are referred to by government officials as "superagencies".
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Those departments that are directly under the other independently elected officers work separately from these superagencies.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The California State Legislature consists of a 40-member Senate and 80-member Assembly.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Senators serve four-year terms and Assembly members two.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Members of the Assembly are subject to term limits of six terms, and members of the Senate are subject to term limits of three terms.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California's legal system is explicitly based upon English common law but carries many features from Spanish civil law, such as community property.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Capital punishment is a legal form of punishment and the state has the largest "Death Row" population in the country (though Oklahoma and Texas are far more active in carrying out executions).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California has performed 13 executions since 1976, with the last being in 2006.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California's judiciary system is the largest in the U.S. with a total of 1,600 judges (the federal system has only about 840).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] At the apex is the seven-member Supreme Court of California, while the California Courts of Appeal serve as the primary appellate courts and the California Superior Courts serve as the primary trial courts.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Justices of the Supreme Court and Courts of Appeal are appointed by the governor, but are subject to retention by the electorate every 12 years.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The administration of the state's court system is controlled by the Judicial Council, composed of the chief justice of the California Supreme Court, 14 judicial officers, four representatives from the State Bar of California, and one member from each house of the state legislature.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In fiscal year 2020–2021, the state judiciary's 2,000 judicial officers and 18,000 judicial branch employees processed approximately 4.4 million cases.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California has an extensive system of local government that manages public functions throughout the state.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Like most states, California is divided into counties, of which there are 58 (including San Francisco) covering the entire state.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Most urbanized areas are incorporated as cities.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] School districts, which are independent of cities and counties, handle public education.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Many other functions, such as fire protection and water supply, especially in unincorporated areas, are handled by special districts.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Per Article 11, Section 1, of the Constitution of California, they are the legal subdivisions of the state.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In addition, the county serves as the local government for all unincorporated areas.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Each county is governed by an elected board of supervisors.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Incorporated cities and towns in California are either charter or general-law municipalities.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] General-law municipalities owe their existence to state law and are consequently governed by it; charter municipalities are governed by their own city or town charters.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Municipalities incorporated in the 19th century tend to be charter municipalities.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] All ten of the state's most populous cities are charter cities.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Most small cities have a council–manager form of government, where the elected city council appoints a city manager to supervise the operations of the city.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Some larger cities have a directly elected mayor who oversees the city government.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In many council-manager cities, the city council selects one of its members as a mayor, sometimes rotating through the council membership—but this type of mayoral position is primarily ceremonial.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The Government of San Francisco is the only consolidated city-county in California, where both the city and county governments have been merged into one unified jurisdiction.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] About 1,102 school districts, independent of cities and counties, handle California's public education.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California school districts may be organized as elementary districts, high school districts, unified school districts combining elementary and high school grades, or community college districts.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] There are about 3,400 special districts in California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] A special district, defined by California Government Code § 16271(d) as "any agency of the state for the local performance of governmental or proprietary functions within limited boundaries", provides a limited range of services within a defined geographic area.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The geographic area of a special district can spread across multiple cities or counties, or could consist of only a portion of one.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Most of California's special districts are *single-purpose districts*, and provide one service.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The state of California sends 52 members to the House of Representatives, the nation's largest congressional state delegation.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Consequently, California also has the largest number of electoral votes in national presidential elections, with 54.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The former speaker of the House of Representatives is the representative of California's 20th district, Kevin McCarthy.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In response to the 2025 Texas redistricting, Governor Newsom secured legislative approval of California Proposition 50 in August 2025, which would redraw the state's congressional districts.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The proposition was approved by 64.4% of voters, adding as many as five seats for the Democratic Party for the 2026 midterms.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Department of Defense had a total of 117,806 active duty servicemembers of which 88,370 were Sailors or Marines, 18,339 were Airmen, and 11,097 were Soldiers, with 61,365 Department of Defense civilian employees.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Additionally, there were a total of 57,792 Reservists and Guardsman in California.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In 2010, Los Angeles County was the largest origin of military recruits in the U.S. by county, with 1,437 individuals enlisting in the military.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] However, as of 2002, Californians were relatively under-represented in the military as a proportion to its population.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In 2000, California, had 2,569,340 veterans of U.S. military service.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] As of 2010, there were 1,942,775 veterans living in California, of which 1,457,875 served during a period of armed conflict, and just over four thousand served before World War II (the largest population of this group of any state).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California's military forces consist of the Army and Air National Guard, the naval and state military reserve (militia), and the California Cadet Corps.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California has an idiosyncratic political culture compared to the rest of the country, and is sometimes regarded as a trendsetter.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In socio-cultural mores and national politics, Californians are perceived as more liberal than other Americans, especially those who live in the inland states.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In the 2016 U.S. presidential election, California had the third highest percentage of Democratic votes behind the District of Columbia and Hawaii.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In the 2020 U.S. presidential election, it had the 6th highest behind D.C., Vermont, Massachusetts, Maryland, and Hawaii.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] According to the Cook Political Report, California contains five of the 15 most Democratic congressional districts in the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California was the second state to recall their state governor, the second state to legalize abortion, and the only state to ban marriage for gay couples twice by vote (including Proposition 8 in 2008).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Voters also passed Proposition 71 in 2004 to fund stem cell research, making California the second state to legalize stem cell research, and Proposition 14 in 2010 to completely change the state's primary election process.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California has also experienced disputes over water rights; and a tax revolt, culminating with the passage of Proposition 13 in 1978, limiting state property taxes.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California voters have rejected affirmative action on multiple occasions, most recently in November 2020.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The state's trend towards the Democratic Party and away from the Republican Party can be seen in state elections.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] From 1899 to 1939, California had exclusively Republican governors.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Several political movements have advocated for California independence.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The California National Party and the California Freedom Coalition both advocate for California independence along the lines of progressivism and civic nationalism.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The Yes California movement attempted to organize an independence referendum via ballot initiative for 2019, which was then postponed.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] The Democrats also hold a supermajority in both houses of the state legislature.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] There are 62 Democrats and 18 Republicans in the Assembly; and 32 Democrats and eight Republicans in the Senate.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] From 1952 through 1988, California was a Republican-leaning state, as the party carried the state's electoral votes in nine of ten elections, with 1964 as the sole exception.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Southern California Republicans Richard Nixon and Ronald Reagan were both elected twice as the 37th and 40th U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] However, Democrats have won all of California's electoral votes for the last eight elections, starting in 1992.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] House, the Democrats held a 34–19 edge in the California delegation of the 110th U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] As the result of gerrymandering, the districts in California were usually dominated by one or the other party, and few districts were considered competitive.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In 2008, Californians passed Proposition 20 to empower a 14-member independent citizen commission to redraw districts for both local politicians and Congress.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] After the 2012 elections, when the new system took effect, Democrats gained four seats and held a 38–15 majority in the delegation.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Following the 2018 midterm House elections, Democrats won 46 out of 53 congressional house seats in California, leaving Republicans with seven.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In general, Democratic strength is centered in the populous coastal regions of the Los Angeles metropolitan area and the San Francisco Bay Area.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Republican strength is still greatest in eastern parts of the state.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Orange County had remained largely Republican until the 2016 and 2018 elections, in which a majority of the county's votes were cast for Democratic candidates.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] One study ranked Berkeley, Oakland, Inglewood and San Francisco in the top 20 most liberal American cities; and Bakersfield, Orange, Escondido, Garden Grove, and Simi Valley in the top 20 most conservative cities.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] In October 2022, out of the 26,876,800 people eligible to vote, 21,940,274 people were registered to vote.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] Of the people registered, the three largest registered groups were Democrats (10,283,258), Republicans (5,232,094), and No Party Preference (4,943,696).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California retains the death penalty, though it has not been used since 2006.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/california-p03] California is a member of the Commission of the Californias, a tri-lateral forum for cooperation between the U.S. state of California and the Mexican states of Baja California and Baja California Sur.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] A **company** or **"yellow" union** is a worker organization which is dominated or unduly influenced by an employer and is therefore not an independent trade union.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Company unions are contrary to international labour law (see ILO Convention 98, Article 2).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] They were outlawed in the United States by the 1935 National Labor Relations Act §8(a)(2), due to their use as agents for interference with independent unions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] However, company unions persist in many countries.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] A "company union" is generally recognized as being an organization that is not freely elected by the workforce, and over which an employer exerts some form of control.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] The International Labour Organization defines a company union as "A union limited to a single company which dominates or strongly influences it, thereby limiting its influence." Under the ILO Right to Organise and Collective Bargaining Convention, 1949 (No.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] 98) Article 2 effectively prohibits any form of company union.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] The first yellow union in France, the Fédération nationale des Jaunes de France ("National Federation of the Yellows of France") was created by Pierre Biétry in 1902.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] The yellow color was deliberately chosen in opposition to the red color associated with socialism.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Yellow unions, in opposition to red unions such as the Confédération Générale du Travail, rejected class struggle and favored the collaboration of capital and labor, and were opposed to strikes.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] According to Zeev Sternhell, the yellow union of Biétry had a membership of about a third of that of the Confédération Générale du Travail, and was funded by corporate interests.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Moreover, also according to Sternhell, there were close relationships between Pierre Biétry and Maurice Barrès and the *Action Française*, making the yellow union of Biétry a precursor of fascist corporatism.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] During the Nazi occupation of France, unions were banned and replaced by corporations organized along the fascist model by the Vichy Regime.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] The labor secretary of Philippe Pétain's administration from 1940 to 1942 was René Belin.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] After the war, René Belin was involved in 1947 with the creation of the Confédération du Travail indépendant (CTI), renamed Confédération Générale des Syndicats Indépendants (CGSI) in 1949 as the original acronym was already used by Confédération des Travailleurs intellectuels.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] The movement was joined by former members of the Confédération des syndicats professionnels français, a union created by François de La Rocque in 1936.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] The CGSI declared that it was formed by "des hommes d’origine et de formation différentes [qui] se sont trouvés d’accord pour dénoncer la malfaisance de la CGT communisée" (men of different origins who agreed to denounce the malfeasance of the communist CGT).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] CGSI developed mostly in the automobile industry, for instance in the Simca factory of Poissy.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] In 1959, the CGSI became the Confédération Française du Travail (CFT), led by Jacques Simakis.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] It was declared a representative union on January 7, 1959, but the decision was overturned by the State Council on April 11, 1962, following a lawsuit by the Confédération Française des Travailleurs Chrétiens (CFTC) based on the funding of CFT by companies.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] In 1968, it organized demonstrations for the "freedom to work" to oppose the strikes organized by the CGT.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] In September 1975, Simakis resigned and denounced the links of CFT with the Service d'Action Civique.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] On June 4, 1977, a commando formed by members of the CFT-Citroën opened fire on strikers at the Verreries mécaniques champenoises in Reims (then directed by Maurice Papon) in a drive-by shooting, killing Pierre Maître, a member of the CGT.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Two other members of the CGT were injured.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Following this incident, the CFT changed its name into Confédération des Syndicats Libres (CSL).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] In the continuity of the company union of Biétry, the CSL is in favor of the association of capital and labor, is opposed to Marxism and collectivism, and denounces the French Communist Party as a civil war machine.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] The number of adherents of CSL was never published, but in professional elections, it obtained from 2% to 4% of the votes.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] In October 2002, the CSL disappeared as a national union as a result of lack of funds.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] It called its supporters to join the Force Ouvrière union in the professional elections.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] In the automobile industry, the CSL remains as the *Syndicat Indépendant de l'Automobile* (Independent Automobile Workers' Union).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Company unions were common in the United States during the early twentieth century, but were outlawed under the 1935 National Labor Relations Act § 8(a)(2) so that trade unions could remain independent of management.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] All labor organizations would have to be freely elected by the workforce, without interference.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] In 1914, 16 miners and family members (and one national guardsman) were killed when the Colorado National Guard attacked a tent colony of striking coal miners in Ludlow, Colorado.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] This event, known as the Ludlow massacre, was a major public relations debacle for mine owners, and one of them—John D.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Rockefeller Jr.—hired labor-relations expert and former Canadian Minister of Labour William Lyon Mackenzie King to suggest ways to improve the tarnished image of his company, Colorado Fuel and Iron.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] One of the elements of the Rockefeller Plan was to form a union, known as the Employee Representation Plan (ERP), based inside the company itself.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] The ERP allowed workers to elect representatives, who would then meet with company officials to discuss grievances.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] In 1933 the miners voted to be represented by the UMW, ending the ERP at Colorado Fuel and Iron.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Company unions, however, continued to operate at other mines in Pueblo, Colorado and Wyoming, and the ERP model was being used by numerous other companies.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] In 1935, the National Labor Relations Act (also known as the Wagner Act) was passed, dramatically changing labor law in the United States.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] In the mid-20th century, managers of high-tech industry like Robert Noyce (who co-founded Fairchild Semiconductor in 1957 and Intel in 1968) worked to rid their organizations of union interference.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] "Remaining non-union is an essential for survival for most of our companies," Noyce once said.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] One way of forestalling unions while obeying the Wagner Act was the introduction of "employee involvement (EI) programs" and other in-house job-cooperation groups.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] One company included them in their "Intel values," cited by employees as reasons why they didn't need a union.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] With workers integrated (at least on a project level) into the decision-making structure, the independent union is seen by some as an anachronism.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Pat Hill-Hubbard, senior vice-president of the American Electronics Association, said in 1994: "Unions as they have existed in the past are no longer relevant.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Labor law of 40 years ago is not appropriate to 20th century economics." Author David Bacon calls EI programs "the modern company union".
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] In 1995, pursuant to a report from the Commission on the Future of Worker-Management Relations, Republicans in the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Congress introduced and voted for the Teamwork for Employees and Managers Act of 1995 (known as the "TEAM Act").
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] The bill would have weakened federal regulations against employer establishment and control of employee involvement programs.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Although the bill indicated that EI plans should not be used specifically to discredit or prevent union organization, trade unions in the United States vehemently opposed the bill.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Jim Wood, an AFL–CIO leader in Los Angeles, said the "Team Act actually would take us backward to the days of company unions." President Bill Clinton vetoed the bill on 30 July 1996.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Calls to legalize company unions are rare, but New York University law professor Richard Epstein, in an opinion piece published in *The Wall Street Journal* on September 11, 2018, called for the repeal of Section 8(a)(2) of the NLRA.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Trade unions in the People's Republic of China are often identified as *government unions*, by virtue of their frequent close relationship with national planning bodies.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] In many Post-Soviet states, including the Russian Federation, the economic collapse of the early 1990s brought a sharp decline in labor activity.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] As a result, official union structures often function as *de facto* company unions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Company unions are a mainstay of labor organization in Japan, viewed with much less animosity than in Europe or the United States.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Unaffiliated with RENGO (the largest Japanese trade union federation), company unions appeal to both the lack of class consciousness in Japanese society and the drive for social status, which is often characterized by loyalty to one's employer.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] The Hong Kong Federation of Trade Unions (HKFTU), as both a political party and a federations of different trade unions in Hong Kong, has been adapting a political stand which are mostly inclined to the Hong Kong and Beijing Government.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Therefore, HKFTU is sometimes classified as a company union, and a Pro-Beijing political party.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] In the 1930s, unions in Mexico organized the Confederation of Mexican Workers (*Confederación de Trabajadores de México*, CTM).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] The state of Nuevo Leon, however, coordinated its workers into *sindicatos blancos* ("white unions"), company unions controlled by corporations in the industrialized region.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] In 1997, the government of Guatemala received a loan for 13 million USD from the World Bank to privatize its seaport, electrical grid, and telephone and postal services.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Canada Post International Limited (CPIL), a subsidiary of Canada Post, and its partner International Postal Services (IPS), was contracted to manage the privatization process.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] In anticipation of union resistance, CPIL-IPS agents reportedly used company unions, along with bribery and death threats, to ensure a smooth transition.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Company unions are also prevalent among the *maquiladoras* in Guatemala.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Supporters of independent trade unions contend that company unions face a conflict of interest, as they are less likely to propose large-scale pro-worker changes to employment contracts—such as overtime rules and salary schedules—than independent unions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] At least one economist advances the idea that in the first part of the 20th century, many companies were hesitant to adopt the company union model for fear that it might lead to support for an independent trade union.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] A 2002 World Bank publication cites research from Malaysia and India which produced conflicting results as to the wage differential provided by trade unions compared to company unions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Malaysia saw improved wages through independent unions, while India did not.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Proponents of company unions claim they are more efficient in responding to worker grievances than independent trade unions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] Proponents also note that independent trade unions do not necessarily have the company's best interests at heart; company unions are designed to resolve disputes within the framework of maximum organizational (not just company) profitability.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] For example, economist Leo Wolman wrote in 1924: "[T]he distinction ... between trade unions and other workmen's associations is frequently a vague and changing one.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/company-union] This insistence against the legitimacy of independent worker agency often extends beyond the confines of the workplace, and company or accommodationist unions often seek to dispute the legitimacy of the trade union movement as a political movement at large.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] Established in 1967 as **Greenwood Press, Inc.**, and based in Westport, Connecticut, GPG published reference works under its Greenwood Press imprint; and scholarly, professional, and general-interest books under its related imprint, Praeger Publishers (/ˈpreɪɡər/).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] Also part of GPG was Libraries Unlimited, which published professional works for librarians and teachers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] Both of the latter became stand-alone imprints of ABC-Clio, in 2008–2009, after its purchase of GPG.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] The company was founded as Greenwood Press, Inc.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] (GPI) in 1967 by Harold Mason, a librarian and antiquarian bookseller, and Harold Schwartz, who had a background in trade publishing.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] In 1969, the company was sold to Williamhouse-Regency, a paper and stationery manufacturing company then on the American Stock Exchange, which led to further expanding its reprint activities as well as starting a microform publishing imprint, **Greenwood Microforms**.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] By 1970, the company established a small scholarly monograph project.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] The same year, Robert Hagelstein, formerly with the Johnson Reprint Corporation division of Academic Press, was hired as vice-president.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] In 1973, Mason and Schwartz left the company, and Hagelstein was named president, a position he would hold until his retirement at the end of 1999.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] During those twenty-seven years, the press wound down its reprint activities, diverting its focus to new scholarly, reference, and professional books.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] This large-scale redirection of the company resulted in the publication of more than 10,000 titles during those years.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] On August 25, 1976, the company was sold to the Congressional Information Service (CIS).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] In 1979, it became part of the Dutch publishing giant Elsevier following the latter's purchase of CIS.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] That same year, the Greenwood subsidiary initiated its **Quorum Books** imprint, which published professional titles in business and law.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] On January 1, 1986, GPI expanded further when it purchased Praeger Publishers (founded in 1950 as Frederick A.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] Praeger, Inc.) from CBS, Inc.; and again in 1989 when it acquired **Bergin & Garvey** and **Auburn House**.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] At the beginning of 1990, the company's name was changed from Greenwood Press, Inc., to Greenwood Publishing Group, Inc.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] When Elsevier merged with Reed International in 1993, GPG became part of Reed Elsevier, and by the mid-1990s the operational part of GPG joined with Heinemann USA, which had been part of Reed.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] When Hagelstein retired at the end of 1999, Wayne Smith was named president.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] Under Smith, GPG made a number of additional acquisitions including the Ablex Publishing, **Oryx Press**, and Libraries Unlimited imprints, and expanded GPG's online and CD-ROM products under its **Greenwood Electronic Media** imprint.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] On July 12, 2001, Reed Elsevier completed its acquisition of Harcourt.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] Harcourt became a wholly owned subsidiary of Reed Elsevier and GPG became part of Harcourt Education.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] On December 13, 2007, GPG became part of Houghton Mifflin Company as a result of Houghton's acquisition of Harcourt.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] On October 1, 2008, ABC-Clio and Houghton Mifflin Harcourt (HMH) announced an agreement granting ABC-Clio a perpetual license to use the imprints and publish the titles of Greenwood Publishing.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] (GPG), including Greenwood Publishing, Praeger Publishers (including **Praeger Security International**), and Libraries Unlimited.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] In addition, HMH would also transfer certain assets, including copyrights, contracts, and inventory, of Greenwood Publishing Group to ABC-Clio.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] This agreement became effective immediately.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] The 88 Post Road West office in Westport, Connecticut, was closed as a result; layoffs began in December 2008.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] The transfer of GPG to ABC-Clio occurred during 2009.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/greenwood-press] In December 2021, Bloomsbury Publishing bought ABC-Clio and with it Greenwood.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The International Longshore and Warehouse Union is dominant on the West Coast, western Canada, Alaska, and Hawaii.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] While longshoremen in the United States had organized and conducted strikes before there was a United States, the first modern longshoremen's union, the Longshoremen's Union Protective Association (LUPA), was formed in the port of New York in 1864.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA traces its origins to a union of longshoremen on the Great Lakes: the Association of Lumber Handlers, founded in 1877, then renamed the National Longshoremen's Association of the United States in 1892.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Organized and led by an Irish tugboat worker named Daniel Keefe, the organization had as many as 100,000 members on the Great Lakes, the East Coast, the West Coast, and the Gulf Coast in 1905.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] From the outset, Keefe faced significant challenges, most notably the outright hostility of Chicago's influential industrialists to unions and the traditional anti-union leanings of longshore recruits from small Midwestern towns.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Nevertheless, Keefe successfully expanded membership in the newborn union to include large numbers of dockworkers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] As the start of the twentieth century loomed, the ILA had approximately 50,000 members, almost all on the Great Lakes.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] By 1905, membership had doubled to 100,000, half of which were scattered throughout the rest of the country.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] ILA leaders focused on eliminating independent stevedoring firms and securing closed shop contracts.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Keefe bargained with employers, guaranteeing uninterrupted work in return for badly needed improvements in working conditions and wage increases.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Keefe retired as President of the ILA in 1908, succeeded by another Great Lakes tugboat man, T.V.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] O'Connor's presidency spanned twelve of the ILA's most tumultuous years.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] In 1909, a bitter three-year strike on the Great Lakes pitted the employers' Lake Carriers Association against every maritime union except the ILA, whose locals voted against participation because it was clear to them that the strike was a losing battle.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] So powerful and well equipped was the Lake Carriers Association that Lakes shipping ran almost regularly despite the union walkout.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] In the end, the ILA was almost alone on the Lakes.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The 1914 absorption of LUPA into the ILA prompted the creation of the ILA's New York District Council and ignited an intense period of growth for the union, both in terms of size and power.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The organization of coastwise longshoremen in 1916 was a significant victory that greatly improved the ILA's position in negotiations: shippers no longer had the option of diverting freight from striking ports along the Atlantic.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] A similar coastwide strike also occurred on the West Coast in 1916, but ended in defeat for the Union.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] As the ILA grew, power shifted increasingly to the Port of New York, where the International established its branch headquarters.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Ryan was organizing longshoremen as an officer of the ILA's New York District Council and, in 1918, as president of the ILA's "Atlantic Coast District".
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA in New York faced a number of internal divisions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] By the turn of the century the ILA had separate Italian, Greek, African-American, German and Irish local unions in New York, reflecting the hiring patterns in the industry, in which foremen typically hired members of their ethnic group.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] In 1912 Italian-Americans made up roughly a third of the workforce, primarily in Brooklyn, while the Irish dominated the Chelsea docks in Manhattan.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Irish dockworkers also had more of the dock and deck jobs in Manhattan, leaving the harder work in the hold to others; Italian dockworkers did the same in Brooklyn, spurning the dirty work of unloading banana boats, which fell to Black dockworkers instead.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA was also riven by internal factionalism.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] O'Connor, who had reluctantly accepted the award, denounced the strike, which he blamed on radicals from the Maritime Transport Workers' Industrial Union (MTW), an arm of the Industrial Workers of the World (IWW).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] O'Connor's most serious opposition, however, did not come from the IWW, but from equally conservative members of the ILA leadership and rivals who had been part of LUPA.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] They succeeded in pushing O'Connor aside, then, having achieved their personal political goals, urged members to return to work while they pursued talks as part of a Special Conciliation Commission appointed by the Mayor.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The strike, which was already collapsing as some local unions returned to work, achieved nothing.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] In addition the ILA faced external competition, particularly from the IWW, which had a number of members on the West Coast, where many workers moved into longshoring from other centers of IWW strength, such as the lumber and mining industries.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The IWW was also strong in Philadelphia during these years, despite efforts to convict the leaders of Local 8 of the IWW on charges of espionage during World War I and the prosecution and conviction of many of the IWW's national leaders in 1919.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] An employer lockout in 1922 largely destroyed the organization.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA likewise faced strong from opposition from employers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The shipping companies on the West Coast, where a few lines dominated the industry, took a particularly hard line, demanding the open shop as early as 1914.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Their intransigence may well have encouraged the growth of the MTW, as well as the influence of IWW radicals within the ILA on the West Coast.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Anthony Chlopek, the last of the Great Lakes presidents, was elected ILA International president and Ryan served as his First Vice president for the six years of Chlopek's presidency.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Perhaps the most significant development during Chlopek's term was the institution of the Prohibition Enforcement Law.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Ryan was elected International president in 1927.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Longshore work, particularly in the port of New York where thousands of longshoremen worked only a day or less in an average week, was largely casual and irregular; many workers earned less than what authorities considered the minimum necessary to support a family.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Longshore work became even more precarious during the Great Depression, as masses of unemployed workers seeking longshore work nearly doubled the available pool of workers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Employers took advantage of these conditions to reduce wages further and establish company unions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Membership soared, increasing as much as sixfold in as many years in some districts.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The process of rebuilding the union was not without hurdles.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Ryan and the union's regional and local leaders regained much of the lost ground, but often at the cost of diminished centralization.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The most dramatic example of this was on the Pacific coast.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA Pacific Coast District was led by the left-leaning Harry Bridges and his associates, known as the "Albion Hall group", who rebelled against Ryan's leadership during the 1934 West Coast longshore strike.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] A network of union activists largely circumvented Ryan during the strike, first organizing the membership to reject the contract that Ryan had negotiated, then leading a strike over his objections.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Bridges and other veterans of the strike replaced Ryan loyalists in union elections up and down the West Coast following the strike.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Ryan never trusted Bridges, even though he was forced to make him an International officer in recognition of his de facto power on the West Coast.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Ryan fired Bridges in 1936, however, after Bridges launched an East Coast speaking tour in support of the left-wing sailors' union, the National Maritime Union, with which Ryan had unfriendly relations.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Bridges subsequently took all but three of the ILA's West Coast locals out of the ILA to form the International Longshore and Warehouse Union, which joined the Congress of Industrial Organizations shortly thereafter.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The war had unexpected effects on the ILA's members' relations with both their employers and their union.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] On the one hand, the ILA, in the name of aiding the war effort, relaxed the rules that had restricted the size of loads that longshoremen could handle, making work harder and more dangerous.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] On the other hand, as more and more workers left the docks either to enlist or to find other jobs in the defense industry, the remaining workers received more steady work and less of the casual daily work offered through the shapeup.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] These workers were more willing to launch wildcat strikes and other challenges to their employers and the ILA leadership.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] This new defiance boiled over in October 1945, as returning veterans played a key role in a citywide wildcat strike to reject the contract negotiated by Ryan.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] ILA members went out on another wildcat strike in 1947, then again in 1948 and again in 1951.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Organized crime figures had been involved in the longshore industry and the ILA from the early years of the twentieth century.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Paul Vaccarelli, an Italian immigrant who boxed under the name "Paul Kelly", led the Five Points Gang, a largely Irish-American street gang from the Five Points neighborhood of Southern Manhattan, with protection from Tammany Hall.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Vaccarelli was also a Vice-President of the ILA who took over leadership of the rank-and-file rebellion against the "Woolworth raise" in 1919.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] In the next generation Eddie McGrath, an Irish-American gangster who worked as an enforcer for the ILA on the Hell's Kitchen waterfront and controlled the docks on the West Side of Manhattan in the 1930s and 1940s, became an important liaison within the ILA to organized crime figures.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] He was a close ally of powerful organized crime figures such as Joe Adonis, Albert Anastasia, and Meyer Lansky.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Individuals who would go on to become important figures in the American Mafia began infiltrating the ILA in those early years.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Emil Camarda, a cousin of Vincent Mangano, took over six Brooklyn longshore locals; he later became an International Vice-President of the ILA.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Vincent Mangano was the head of one of the Five Families that controlled much of organized crime in New York.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Anthony Anastasio, a member of the Mangano crime family, was the President of ILA Local 1814, the largest local within the ILA; he also became an International Vice-President of the ILA in 1937.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Anastasio's brother, Albert Anastasia, was head of the organization known as Murder, Inc., as well as serving as Mangano's underboss and his eventual successor as head of the Mangano crime family after Mangano's disappearance in 1951.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Anthony Scotto, Anastasio's son-in-law, succeeded him as President of Local 1814 upon Anastasio's death in 1963 and later became the ILA general organizer, one of the three highest positions in the ILA.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] That plan to make Scotto International President was prevented, however, by his conviction for accepting bribes from waterfront employers and related racketeering charges.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] After Castellano's murder in 1985, new family boss John Gotti replaced Scotto with another mobster from Brooklyn's Red Hook neighborhood, Anthony Ciccone.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Ciccone later agreed to resign his posts with Local 1841 as part of a consent decree to resolve the federal government's RICO suit against Scotto, Local 1814 and other individuals and ILA locals; this decree also barred Ciccone from participating in any ILA or waterfront activities.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] In 2003 Ciccone was convicted on charges of exerting illegal control over ILA locals 1 and 1814, in violation of the 1991 consent decree, as well as related RICO charges.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The Genovese crime family took on a greater role in ILA and waterfront affairs as the industry relocated in the 1970s from Manhattan and Brooklyn to the Staten Island and New Jersey docks, which could handle the new shipping containers more efficiently.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The US government has twice attempted, but failed, to prove that Harold Daggett, the International President of the ILA, was a Genovese associate.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Daggett has denied that there is any substantial remaining Mob influence on the docks.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The waterfront provided multiple sources of income for the Mafia.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] They would extract tribute from shipping companies by threatening to prevent cargo from being loaded or unloaded.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] They also received kickbacks from ILA members through their control of the working foremen appointed by the union who would choose which workers to hire through the shapeup, in which casual workers were hired on a daily basis.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] That also gave the mob leverage to squeeze longshoremen who depended on that foreman for work by requiring them to take out loans at usurious rates if they wanted to be hired.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Finally, they could use their influence within a local union to create no-show jobs for their associates and loot the local's treasury and benefit funds.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The Mafia also used violence to eliminate opponents within the Union: Pete Panto, an outspoken critic of Ryan, was reportedly killed on Anastasia's orders in 1939, while McGrath and his associates assaulted and sometimes killed others.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] These practices received widespread attention in 1952 after the board of inquiry appointed by New York State Industrial Commissioner Edward Corsi to investigate the causes of the 1951 wildcat strike released its report, detailing the pervasive role that organized crime played in the ILA's affairs.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Dewey ordered his New York State Crime Commission to conduct a full investigation of the ILA; it held public hearings regarding conditions on the New York waterfront.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The states of New York and New Jersey subsequently created the Waterfront Commission of New York Harbor in 1953 to oversee the waterfront.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Following these public hearings, in February, 1953, the Executive Council of the AFL demanded, under the threat of expulsion, that the ILA take appropriate steps to eliminate corruption.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The Council's view was that the testimony before the Crime Commission provided clear and definite indication that the worker members in the Port of New York were being exploited and were not receiving the protection which they had a right to expect.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The Executive Council singled out the evils stemming from the "shape-up" method of hiring, the acceptance of gifts and bribes by union officers from employers, the prevalence of union officers with criminal records, and the lack of democracy in the local unions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The Executive Council did not hold any hearings of its own.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] After an exchange of correspondence and the appearance of ILA representatives before the Executive Council, the Council concluded that ILA had failed to take the necessary remedial action to eliminate the condemned conditions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA was advised that the Council would recommend to the AFL Annual Convention that the ILA be suspended until it had taken the necessary action to comply in good faith with the Council's request.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] At the AFL Annual Convention held in September, 1953, on the recommendation of the Executive Council, the ILA's charter was revoked by a vote of 79,079 to 736.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The AFL declared that the ILA had "permitted gangsters, racketeers and thugs to fasten themselves to the body of its organization, infecting it with corruption and destroying its integrity, its effectiveness and its trade-union character".
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] While Ryan had been named "Lifetime President" in 1945, he resigned in 1953, following the ILA's expulsion from the AFL.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Bradley was elected to the presidency of the ILA-Independent at the November 1953 convention.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] At this same Convention the AFL voted to charter a new organization, the International Brotherhood of Longshoremen (IBL), to organize longshoremen and, in particular, those represented by the ILA.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] In response the ILA sent Thomas "Teddy" Gleason, ILA General Organizer, from port to port nationwide.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Meanwhile, 17,000 longshoremen voted in the National Labor Relations Board (NLRB) election on December 24 and 25, 1953 to determine which union would represent longshoremen in the Port of New York.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA was victorious, but Governor Dewey immediately initiated a campaign to overturn the election results.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Tension on the New York piers was mounting.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] ILA loyalists and many other longshoremen were at best suspicious of the IBL, which they viewed as a tool of the Waterfront Commission and a scab union—an organization of workers perceived as having a role in strikebreaking.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] By early March 1954, the storm finally hit when Teamster President Dave Beck was perceived as betraying the ILA by refusing to cross an IBL picket line.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] News spread and on piers up and down Manhattan ILA longshoremen refused to handle Teamster deliveries and walked off the docks in a wildcat strike.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] An NLRB injunction forbade ILA leaders from striking or disrupting freight transportation.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Violence erupted as the IBL, facilitated by the police and Beck's Teamsters, smashed picket lines.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Then the NLRB examiner effectively overturned the December elections.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] This proved to be the last straw, for less than a week later, Bradley made the ILA strike official.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Other unions and workers supported the ILA, including a major Teamsters local, which indicated Beck's opposition to the ILA strikers was not shared throughout the rest of the Teamsters.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The balance of power began to shift as Gleason gained ground against the IBL and longshoremen along the coast refused to handle diverted cargo.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Dewey's anti-ILA entourage responded to the shift with a series of legal actions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Then, the NLRB officially set aside the results of the December elections and called for a new vote.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The final blow, however, was the NLRB's announcement that the ILA would be banned from future elections unless it ended the work stoppage "forthwith".
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Bradley had no choice but to send his men back to work.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA won a slim victory in the May 26, 1954 election, despite aggressive IBL campaigning.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] In August 1954, the results were finally approved and certified by NLRB, and thus the ILA was given representational rights in the Port of New York.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The IBL did not go quietly, and forced a third representational election in 1956, in which it was again defeated.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] By the time an AFL–CIO committee recommended re-admittance for the ILA in August 1959, the IBL was active only in the Great Lakes.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] In October, the IBL officially dissolved itself and IBL president Larry Long became president of ILA's Great Lakes District.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Gleason was unanimously elected president at the ILA International Convention in 1963.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Gleason moved the headquarters to its current location in New Jersey and worked on improving the union's financial affairs.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] In 1953 the states of New York and New Jersey entered into an interstate compact, with Congressional approval, that established a Waterfront Commission responsible for regulating the ILA by preventing individuals with a criminal record from holding positions within it.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The federal government has made two attempts to use civil RICO suits to rid the union of organized crime's influence, but fallen short on each occasion.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The first case, filed in 1990, was brought against a number of ILA local unions, ILA officers and reputed organized crime figures operating in the New York and New Jersey area.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] But, even so, in the opinion of some observers, those agreements were ineffective, as the Genovese and Gambino crime families remained influential in those local unions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The second RICO action was brought against the International Union, rather than against particular ILA locals; it also named several ERISA benefit funds and a number of individual defendants.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The government has not pursued this effort to impose a trusteeship over the International.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] In 2018, the Waterfront Commission of New York Harbor, which exerted government oversight of the docks in New York and New Jersey, criticized hiring patterns by the ILA.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The "containerization revolution" began in 1955 when former trucking company owner Malcom McLean and engineer Keith Tantlinger developed the modern intermodal container.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] This new method of packing and transporting goods had a drastic impact on longshore work, dramatically reducing the amount of labor required to load and unload cargo and largely eliminating many job functions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILWU was the first US longshore union to address the impact of containerization through the Mechanization and Modernization Agreement of 1960, which applied to ports on the West Coast of the US.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA followed suit in 1965, when the ILA negotiated what was at the time the longest-lasting ILA contract in history and the first truly forward-looking contract the union signed.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] As automation and containerization increased, the contract focused on preserving jobs through initiatives such as the Guaranteed Annual Income (GAI) program and the Job Security Program (JSP).
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Some employers outside New York who faced the loss of business as a result of the agreement challenged the "Rules on Containers" that were negotiated and agreed to by management and labor as a means of preserving jobs.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The National Labor Relations Board originally upheld the challenge, only to be reversed by the United States Supreme Court in two cases in the 1980s that held that the rules were lawful and did not violate federal labor law.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] However, the Federal Trade Commission later found that the Rules were an impermissible restraint on trade.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA has continued to address the impact of containerization and automation of work on the docks.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] In September 2024, in their negotiations with the United States Maritime Alliance, the ILA demanded a total ban on automation of cranes, gates and containers at 36 U.S. ports.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA threatened to strike that month unless they would receive wage hikes and a ban on automation at U.S. ports.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] ILA members were offered a nearly 50% wage hike, triple employer contributions to pension plans, and better health care options while retaining current rules on automation, but the ILA rejected the offer and began a strike in October.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Contemporary accounts attribute the decision to strike to ILA International President Harold Daggett, who had been known as a critic of the Biden administration and who said the strike would "cripple" the economy prior to the 2024 presidential election.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Daggett criticized the labor agreement that the ILWU, the main longshore union on the West Coast, reached in 2023 with the help of the Biden administration, which boosted salaries by 32%, for not doing enough to stop automation.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Later in 2025 the ILA participated in a conference in Lisbon that led to the creation of a “Global Maritime Alliance” of maritime unions joining together to fight any expansion of automating waterfront facilities around the world.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA conducted boycotts aimed at trade with the Soviet Union during periods of crisis, such as the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The Supreme Court ruled in two companion cases in the 1980s that the union's boycott could not be enjoined under the Norris-LaGuardia Act, but that it was an unlawful secondary boycott that violated the Taft-Hartley Act.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA grew out of the union of Great Lakes longshoremen founded by Daniel Keefe in the nineteenth century.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Recent years have seen a significant contraction of the amount of work on the Great Lakes due to containerization and automation and the drop in the amount of foreign cargo moving through the Lakes.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] As a result the ILA Great Lakes District was incorporated into the ILA Atlantic Coast District in 1992.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Greene, who was murdered by other organized crime figures in 1977, was the subject of both a book, *To Kill The Irishman*, and a movie, *Kill the Irishman*.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA has represented Canadian longshoremen since the turn of the twentieth century.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The Canadian Joint Council, founded in 2018, represents all ILA Locals in Canada [Local 269 (Halifax, Nova Scotia); Local 273 (St.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] John's, Newfoundland and Labrador); Local 1976 (Mulgrave, NS); Local 1997 (Oshawa, ON); Local 2020 (Rimouski, QC); Local 2029 (Dalhousie, NB); Local 2033 (Cacouna, QC); Local 2048 (La Malbaie, QC); Local 2054 (Corner Brook, NFLD); and Local 2065 (Sheets Harbour, NS)].
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Boston longshoremen organized the Boston Longshoreman’s Provident Union in either 1847 or 1881.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA became the bargaining representative for Boston longshoremen in 1913, intervening in a failing thirteen-week strike by the BLPU and the Knights of Labor by settling the strike for a three cent per hour wage increase, raising their wages to 33 cents per hour for a ten-hour day.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Once the NYSA and ILA reached agreement on wages and hours of work the "outer port" unions then bargained over their own port conditions, meal hours, damaged cargo rates, and other local issues.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] That pattern began to change in 1931, when Boston longshoremen went out on an eleven-week strike over premium pay when required to work through a meal hour.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The strike became especially bitter when Governor Ely allowed Black strikebreakers to be housed on the Commonwealth Pier, which was state property.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] This move was countermanded by Ely's political rival, Mayor James Michael Curley, who ordered the strikebreakers off the pier as a violation of local sanitation codes.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] There were no Black longshoremen working anywhere in the Boston area as of 1954.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The Boston locals continued bargaining with shippers, signing a "port conditions" agreement in 1935, but then did not sign another agreement until 1950, depending instead on the New York negotiations to provide updated terms, which the Boston employers then formally accepted.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] This lack of a written agreement discouraged shippers from using the Port of Boston.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] It was only with the expulsion of the ILA from the AFL in 1953, which put the ILA in danger of being raided by other unions, that the International forced the Boston locals to resume entering into formal collective bargaining agreements.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The city’s roughly five thousand longshoremen in 1913 were about one-third African-American, a third Irish and Irish-American, and a third Eastern Europeans, especially Lithuanians and Poles.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The IWW included members of each ethnic group on its bargaining team in negotiating with employers and integrated work gangs.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA replaced the IWW on the docks after the 1922 lockout, coupled with attacks on that union by authorities, broke its strength.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Baltimore was the sixth largest port in the world around the start of the twentieth century.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Unlike the Port of New York or Boston, which were dominated by Irish and Italian immigrants, Baltimore's stevedores and longshoremen were overwhelmingly Polish.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] In the 1930s about eighty percent of Baltimore's longshoremen were Polish or of Polish descent.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The port of Baltimore had an international reputation of fast cargo handling credited to the well-organized gang system that was nearly free of corruption, wildcat strikes and constant work stoppages, unlike its East coast counterparts.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The New York Anti-Crime Commission and the Waterfront Commission of New York looked upon the Baltimore system as the ideal one for all ports.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The hiring of longshoremen in Baltimore by the gang system dates back to 1913.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The Polish longshoremen began setting up the system by selecting the most skilled men to lead them.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] This newly formed gang would usually work for the same company, which would give the priority to the gang.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] During times when there was no work within that company the gang would work elsewhere, or even divide to aid other groups in their work, which would speed up the work and would make it more efficient.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] In an environment as dangerous as a busy waterfront, the Baltimore's gangs always operated together as a unit, because the experience let them know what each member would do at any given time making the waterfront a much safer place.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] At the beginning of the Second World War Polish predominance in the Port of Baltimore would significantly diminish as many Poles left to fight the war.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The District Court ordered the merging the two locals and creation of a single hiring hall and seniority list, but did not order elimination of the gang system; the Court of Appeals affirmed.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Black longshoremen have made up nearly the entire workforce on the docks in Charleston, South Carolina for the last half of the 19th century, both before and after emancipation, and since then.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] They established their own union, the Longshoremen Protective Union Association (LPUA), that wielded political influence in both the Republican and Democratic parties of postbellum South Carolina.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The LPUA ceased to exist around the turn of the 19th century.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] In 1936 the ILA chartered Local 1422, a segregated union of Black dockworkers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Local 1422 was at the center of a long legal battle involving the Charleston Five, five longshoremen facing prosecution in 2000 for their involvement with a picket line conflict with local police.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The five were ultimately freed after being held under house arrest for nearly two years while awaiting trial.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA chartered Local 1416, a segregated union restricted to Black longshoremen, in 1936.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] At the time dock workers in Miami-Dade County were being paid thirty cents an hour, one of the lowest wage rates in the country.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Judge Henderson, the founder and first president of the local union, negotiated a collective bargaining agreement that raised employees' wages and went on to be elected International Vice-President of the ILA.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Local 1922, also based in Miami, was run for years by George Barone, the President of Local 1922, an International Vice-President of the ILA, and a member of the Genovese crime family who had been barred from working in the New York-New Jersey Harbor by the Waterfront Commission.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Barone was convicted in 1979 of charges involving extortion, racketeering, obstruction of justice, tax violations and other crimes.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Barone was forced to resign his union offices in 2001, according to a wiretapped conversation involving Arthur Coffey, President of Local 1922, because he had disrespected a son of Vincent Gigante, the head of the Genovese crime family.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Barone subsequently became a cooperating witness for the FBI and the Waterfront Commission.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Barone claimed, among other things, that he had helped engineer Harold Daggett's election as International President of the ILA—a claim that the federal government tried, but failed, to prove in criminal proceedings against Daggett.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA chartered Local 1402 as a segregated Black local in 1935.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Longshoremen obtained representation by Local 1402 in an NLRB election in 1936.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The union won its first labor agreement after striking in 1937.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Local 1402's second President, Perry Harvey Sr., became an important spokesperson for Local 1402's members and the African-American community in Tampa more generally.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] His son succeeded him as President of Local 1402 and was the first Black member of Tampa's City Council.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Like other Southern ports, Mobile, Alabama had segregated locals for White and Black longshoremen; Local 1410, the African-American local, was established in 1936.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] This form of Jim Crow unionism provided for a rough division of work between Black and White longshoremen.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Martin Luther King Jr. made his only public appearance in Mobile in 1959 at Local 1410's union hall, which served as a cultural and political center for the community.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA was one of the few AFL unions in the early twentieth century that not only admitted Black workers as members, but elected them as leaders, although typically within segregated local unions.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Porter of New Orleans was an exception, as he was elected as an International Vice-President of the ILA during these years, despite demands from White longshoremen from New Orleans that a White unionist be elected instead.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Black and White New Orleans longshoremen, organized in separate ILA locals, had long traditions of sharing work on a 50/50 basis, which meant insisting that foremen hire equal numbers of Black and White members of each work gang to prevent employers from playing each group off against the other.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The segregated locals also cooperated in dealing with employers, creating a Dock and Cotton Council in 1901 that brought together unions of black and White screwmen, longshoremen, teamsters, loaders, and other work classifications at the waterfront.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Leadership positions on the council were generally divided according to the 50-50 system, with the presidency and financial secretary position held by White workers and the vice-presidency and corresponding secretary position held by black workers; committee positions were similarly assigned.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] This era of interracial cooperation ended in 1923, when employers broke the Council's strike and the Council itself by importing large numbers of strikebreakers from rural parishes, then imposing the open shop with the assistance of municipal and state governments and the federal courts.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] That defeat meant that neither Black nor White locals had the power they once had to demand equal assignments for White and Black workers.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA chartered two new segregated local unions in New Orleans in 1935: Local 1418 for White dockworkers and Local 1919 for their Black counterparts.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] These two new locals likewise sometimes competed and sometimes cooperated in distributing work between them.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] That same year of 1935 the ILA launched a major strike in New Orleans and other Gulf ports that sought to recover control of dock operations in New Orleans; that strike failed due to the lack of support from the Seamen's Union and opposition from the International Union.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The segregated New Orleans locals finally merged in 1980, due to both the legal indefensibility of segregating locals by race and the loss of work due to the relocation of work to other ports due to New Orleans' failure to modernize to accept containerization.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The port has continued to lose work to other, more modern ports in Gulfport and other nearby communities in the years since then.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] As in other Southern ports, African-American dockworkers have made up a large part of the Houston longshore workforce for more than a century.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] The ILA created segregated locals for Blacks and Whites in Houston, as they did in other Southern ports.
[src:american-society-of-marine-engineers/international-longshoremen-s-association] Rotating work among gangs from the segregated locals also helped toward "decasualization," a reduction in the number of casual laborers.
